\v 24 This is it that helongeth unto the Levites: from twenty and five years old and upward they shall go in to wait upon the service of the tabernacle of the congregation:
\p
\v 25 And from the age of fifty years they shall cease waiting upon the service thereof, and shall serve no more:
\p
\v 26 But shall minister with their brethren in the tabernacle of the congregation, to keep the charge, and shall do no service. Thus shalt thou do unto the Levites touching their charge.
\c 9
\cl CHAPTER 9
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto «Mo- ses in the wilderness of Sinai, in the first month of the second year after they were come out of the land of Egypt, saying,
\p
\v 2 Let the children of Israel also keep the passover at the appointed season.
\p
\v 3 In the fourteenth day of this month, at even, ye shall keep it in the appointed season: according to all the rites of it, and according to all the ceremonies thereof, shall ye keep it.
\p
\v 4 And Moses spake unto the children of Israel, that they should keep the passover.
\p
\v 5 And they kept the passover on the fourteenth day of the first month at even in the wilderness of Sinai: according to all that the LORD commanded Moses, so did the children of Israel.
\p
\v 6 ¶ And there were certain men, who were defiled by the dead body of a man, that they could not keep the passover on that day: and they came before Moses and before Aaron on that day:
\p
\v 7 And those men said unto him, We \add are\add* defiled by the dead body of a man: wherefore are we kept back, that we may not offer an offering of the LORD in the appointed season among the children of Israel?
\p
\v 8 And Moses said unto them, Stand still, and I will hear what the LORD will command concerning you.
\p
\v 9 ¶ And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 10 Speak unto the children of Israel, saying, If any man of you or of your posterity shall be unclean by reason of a dead body, or \add be\add* in a journey afar off, yet he shall keep the passover unto the LORD.
\p
\v 11 The fourteenth day of the second month at even they shall keep it, \add and\add* eat it with unleavened bread and bitter \add herbs.\add*
\p
\v 12 They shall leave none of it unto the morning, nor break any bone of it: according to all the ordinances of the passover they shall keep it.
\p
\v 13 But the man that \add is\add* clean, and is not in a journey, and forbeareth to keep the passover, even the same soul shall be cut off from among his people: because he brought not the offering of the LORD in the appointed season, that man shall bear his sin.
\p
\v 14 And if a stranger shall sojourn among you, and will keep the passover unto the LORD; according to the ordinance of the passover, and according to the custom thereof, so shall he do: ye shall have one ordinance, both for the stranger, and for him that was born in the land.
\p
\v 15 ¶ And on the day that the tabernacle was reared up the cloud covered the tabernacle, \add namely,\add* the tent of the testimony: and at even there was upon the tabernacle as it were the appearance of fire, until the morning.
\p
\v 16 So it was alway: the cloud covered it \add by day,\add* and the appearance of fire by night.
\p
\v 17 And when the cloud was taken up from the tabernacle, then after that the children of Israel journeyed: and in the place where the cloud abode, there the children of Israel pitched their tents.
\p
\v 18 At the commandment of the LORD the children of Israel journeyed, and at the commandment of the LORD they pitched: as long as the cloud abode upon the tabernacle they rested in their tents.
\p
\v 19 And when the cloud tarried long upon the tabernacle many days, then the children of Israel kept the charge of the LORD, and journeyed not.
\p
\v 20 And \add so\add* it was, when the cloud was a few days upon the tabernacle; according to the commandment of the LORD they abode in their tents, and according to the commandment of the LORD they journeyed.
\p
\v 21 And \add so\add* it was, when the cloud abode from even unto the morning, and \add that\add* the cloud was taken up in the morning, then they journeyed: whether \add it was\add* by day or by night that the cloud was taken up, they journeyed.
\p
\v 22 Or \add whether it were\add* two days, or a month, or a year, that the cloud tarried upon the tabernacle, remaining thereon, the children of Israel abode in their tents, and journeyed not: but when it was taken up, they journeyed.
\p
\v 23 At the commandment of the LORD they rested in the tents, and at the commandment of the LORD they journeyed: they kept the charge of the LORD, at the commandment of the LORD by the hand of Moses.
\c 10
\cl CHAPTER 10
\p
\v 1 ¶ And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 2 Make thee two trumpets of silver; of a whole piece shalt thou make them: that thou mayest use them for the calling of the assembly, and for the journeying of the camps.
\p
\v 3 And when they shall blow with them, all the assembly shall assemble themselves to thee at the door of the tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 4 And if they blow \add but\add* with one \add trumpet,\add* then the princes, \add that are\add* heads of the thousands of Israel, shall gather themselves unto thee.
\p
\v 5 When ye blow an alarm, then the camps that lie on the east side shall go forward.
\p
\v 6 When ye blow an alarm the second time, then the camps that lie on the south side shall take their journey: they shall blow an alarm for their journeys.
\p
\v 7 But when the congregation is to be gathered together, ye shall blow, but ye shall not sound an alarm.
\p
\v 8 And the sons of Aaron, the priests, shall blow with the trumpets; and they shall be to you for an ordinance for ever throughout your generations.
\p
\v 9 And if ye go to war in your land against the enemy that oppresseth you, then ye shall blow an alarm with the trumpets; and ye shall be remembered before the LORD your God, and ye shall be saved from your enemies.
\p
\v 10 Also in the day of your gladness, and in your solemn days, and in the beginnings of your months, ye shall blow with the trumpets over your burnt offerings, and over the sacrifices of your peace offerings; that they may be to you for a memorial before your God: I \add am\add* the LORD your God.
\p
\v 11 ¶ And it came to pass on the twentieth \add day\add* of the second month, in the second year, that the cloud was taken up from off the tabernacle of the testimony.
\p
\v 12 And the children of Israel took their journeys out of the wilderness of Sinai; and the cloud rested in the wilderness of Paran.
\p
\v 13 And they first took their journey according to the commandment of the LORD by the hand of Moses.
\p
\v 14 ¶ In the first \add place\add* went the standard of the camp of the children of Judah according to their armies: and over his host \add was\add* Nahshon the son of Amminadab.
\p
\v 15 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Issachar \add was\add* Nethaneel the son of Zuar.
\p
\v 16 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Zebulun \add was\add* Eliab the son of Helon.
\p
\v 17 And the tabernacle was taken down; and the sons of Gershon and the sons of Merari set forward, bearing the tabernacle.
\p
\v 18 ¶ And the standard of the camp of Reuben set forward according to their armies: and over his host \add was\add* Elizur the son of Shedeur.
\p
\v 19 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Simeon was Shelumiel the son of Zurishaddai.
\p
\v 20 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Gad was Eliasaph the son of Deuel.
\p
\v 21 And the Kohathites set forward, bearing the sanctuary: and \add the other\add* did set up the tabernacle against they came.
\p
\v 22 ¶ And the standard of the camp of the children of Ephraim set forward according to their armies: and over his host \add was\add* Elishama the son of Ammihud.
\p
\v 23 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Manasseh \add was\add* Gamaliel the son of Pedahzur.
\p
\v 24 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Benjamin \add was\add* Abidan the son of Gideoni.
\p
\v 25 ¶ And the standard of the camp of the children of Dan set forward, \add which was\add* the rearward of all the camps throughout their hosts: and over his host \add was\add* Ahiezer the son of Ammishaddai.
\p
\v 26 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Asher \add was\add* Pagiel the son of Ocran.
\p
\v 27 And over the host of the tribe of the children of Naphtali \add was\add* Ahira the son of Enan.
\p
\v 28 Thus \add were\add* the journeyings of the children of Israel according to their armies, when they set forward.
\p
\v 29 ¶ And Moses said unto Hobab, the son of Reuel the Midianite, Moses’ father in law, We are journeying unto the place of which the LORD said, I will give it you: come thou with us, and we will do thee good: for the LORD hath spoken good concerning Israel.
\p
\v 30 And he said unto him, I will not go; but I will depart to mine own land, and to my kindred.
\p
\v 31 And he said, Leave us not, I pray thee; forasmuch as thou knowest how we are to encamp in the wilderness, and thou mayest be to us instead of eyes.
\p
\v 32 And it shall be, if thou go with us, yea, it shall be, that what goodness the LORD shall do unto us, the same will we do unto thee.
\p
\v 33 ¶ And they departed from the mount of the LORD three days’ journey: and the ark of the covenant of the LORD went before them in the three days’ journey, to search out a resting place for them.
\p
\v 34 And the cloud of the LORD \add was\add* upon them by day, when they went out of the camp.
\p
\v 35 And it came to pass, when the ark set forward, that Moses said, Rise up, LORD, and let thine enemies be scattered; and let them that hate thee flee before thee.
\p
\v 36 And when it rested, he said, Return, O LORD, unto the many thousands of Israel.
\c 11
\cl CHAPTER 11
\p
\v 1 AND when the people complained, - it displeased the LORD: and the Lord heard it; and his anger was kindled; and the fire of the Lord burnt among them, and consumed fhem that were in the uttermost parts of the camp.
\p
\v 2 And the people cried unto Moses; and when Moses prayed unto the Lord, the fire was quenched.
\p
\v 3 And he called the name of the place Taberah: because the fire of the Lord burnt among them,
\p
\v 4 And the mixed multitude that vjas among them fell a Ousting: and the children of Israel also wept again, and said, Who shall give us flesh to eat?
\p
\v 5 We remember the fish, which we did eat in Egypt freely; the cucumbers, and the melons, and the leeks, and the onions, and the gar lick:
\p
\v 6 But now our soul is dried away: there is nothing at all, beside ttus manna, before our eyes.
\p
\v 7 And the manna was as coriander seed, and the colour thereof as the colour of bdellium.
\p
\v 8 And the people went about, and gathered it, and ground it in mills, or beat it in a mortar, and boiled it in pots, and made cakes of it: and the taste of it was as the taste of cakes mixed with fresh oil.
\p
\v 9 And when the dew fell upon the camp in the night, the manna fell upon it.
\p
\v 10 Then Moses heard the people weep throughout their families, every man in the door of his tent: and the anger of the Lord was kindled greatly; Moses also was displeased.
\p
\v 11 And Moses said unto the LORD, Wherefore hast thou afflicted thy servant ? and wherefore have I not found favour in thy sight, that thou iayest the burden of all this people upon me?
\p
\v 12 Have I conceived all this people? have I brought them to birth, that thou shouldest say unto me. Carry them in thy bosom, as a nursing father beareth the sucking child, unto the land which thou swarest unto their fathers?
\p
\v 13 Whence should I have flesh to give unto ail this people? for they weep unto me, saying, Give us flesh, that we may eat.
\p
\v 14 I am not able to bear all tl\is people alone, because it is too heavy for me.
\p
\v 15 And if thou deal thus with me, kill me, I ipray thee, out of hand, if I have found favour in thy sight; and let me not see my wretchedness.
\p
\v 16 And the LORD said unto Moses, Gather unto me seventy men of the elders of Israel, whom thou knowest to be the elders of the people, and officers over them; and bring them unto the tabernacle of the congregation, that they may stand there with thee.
\p
\v 17 And I will come down and talk with thee there: and I will take of the spirit which is upon thee, and will put it upon them; and they shall bear the burden of the people with thee, that thou bear it not thyself alone.
\p
\v 18 And say thou unto the people, Sanctify yourselves against to morrow, and ye shall eat flesh: for ye have wept in the ears of the LORD, saying, Who shall give us flesh to eat? for it vas well with us in Egypt: therefore the LORD will give you flesh, and ye shall eat.
\p
\v 19 Ye shall not eat one day, nor
\,\NO days, nor five days, neither ten days, nor twenty days;
\p
\v 20 But even a whole month, until it come out at your nostrils, and it be loathsome unto you: because that ye have despised the Lord who is among you, and have wept before him, saying. Why came we forth out of Egypt?
\p
\v 21 And Moses said, The people, among whom I am, are six hundred thousand footmen; and thou hast said, I will give them flesh, that they may eat a whole month.
\p
\v 22 Shall the flocks and the herds be slain for them, to suffice them? or shall all the fish of the sea be gathered together for them, to suffice them?
\p
\v 23 And the LORD said unto Moses, Is the Lord’s hand waxed short? thou Shalt see now whether my word shall come to pass unto thee or not.
\p
\v 24 And Moses went out, and told the people the words of the Lord, and gathered the seventy men of the elders of the people, and set them round about the tabernacle.
\p
\v 25 And the Lord came down in the cloud, and spake unto him, and took of the spirit that was upon him, and gave it unto the seventy elders: and it came to pass, that, when the spirit rested upon them, they prophesied, but not afterward.
\p
\v 26 But there remained two of the men in the camp, the name of the one was Eldad, and the name of the other Medad: and the spirit rested upon them; and they were of them that were written, but went not out unto the tabernacle: and they prophesied in the camp.
\p
\v 27 And there ran a young man, and told Moses, and said, Eldad and Medad do prophesy in the cam.p.
\p
\v 28 And Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of Moses, one of his young men, answered and said, My lord Moses, forbid them.
\p
\v 29 And Moses said unto him, Enviest thou for my sake? would God that all the LORD’S people were prophets, and that the LORD would put his spirit upon them !
\p
\v 30 And Moses gat him into the camp, he and the elders of Israel.
\p
\v 31 And there went forth a wind from the LORD, and brought quails from the sea, and let them fall by the camp, as it were a day’s journey on this side, and as it were a day’s journey on the other side, round about the camp, and as it were two cubits high upon the face of the earth.
\p
\v 32 And the people stood up all that day, and all that night, and all the next day, and they gathered the quails: he that gathered least gathered ten homers: and they spread themall abroad for themselves round about the camp.
\p
\v 33 And while the flesh was yet between their teeth, ere it was chewed, the wrath of the LORD was kindled against the people, and the Lord smote the people with a very great plague.
\p
\v 34 And he called the name of that place 2z Kibroth-hattaavah: because there they buried the people that lusted.
\p
\v 35 And the people journeyed from Kibroth-hattaavah unto Hazeroth; and abode at Hazeroth.
\c 12
\cl CHAPTER 12
\p
\v 1 AND Miriam and Aaron spake against Moses because of the Ethiopian woman whom he had married: for he had married an Ethiopian woman.
\p
\v 2 And they said, Hath the LORD indeed spoken only by Moses? hath he not spoken also by us ? And the Lord heard it.
\p
\v 3 (Now the man Moses was very meek, above all the men which ivere upon the face of the earth.)
\p
\v 4 And the LORD spake suddenly unto Moses, and unto Aaron, and unto Miriam, Come cut ye three unto the itabernacle of the congregation. And they three came out.
\p
\v 5 And the Lord came down in the ■pillar of the cloud, and stood in the:?'door of the tabernacle, and called Aaron and Miriam: and they both came forth.
\p
\v 6 And he said, Hear now my words: If there be a prophet among you, the Lord will make myself known unto him in a vision, and will speak unto him in a dream.
\p
\v 7 My servant Moses is not so, who is faithful in all mine house.
\p
\v 8 With him will I speak mouth to mouth, even openly, and not in dark speeches; and the similitude of the Lord shall he behold: wherefore then were ye not afraid to speak against my servant Moses ?
\p
\v 9 And the anger of the Lord was kindled against them; and he departed.
\p
\v 10 And the cloud departed from off the tabernacle; and, behold, Miriam became leprous, white as snow: and Aaron looked upon Miriam, and, behold, she ivasyieprous.
\p
\v 11 And Aaron said unto Moses, Alas, my lord, I beseech thee, lay not the sin upon us, wherein we have done foolishly, and wherein we have sinned.
\p
\v 12 Let her not be as one dead, of whom the flesh is half consumed when he cometh out of his mother’s womb.
\p
\v 13 And Moses cried unto the Lord, saying, Heal her now, O Grod, I beseech thee.
\p
\v 14 And the LORD said unto Moses, If her father had but spit in her face, should she not be ashamed seven days? let her be shut out from the camp seven days, and after that let her be received in again.
\p
\v 15 And Miriam was shut out from the camp seven days: and the people journeyed not till Miriam was brought in again.
\p
\v 16 And afterward the people removed from Hazeroth, and pitched in the wilderness of Paran.
\c 13
\cl CHAPTER 13
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, - saying,
\p
\v 2 Send thou men, that they may search the land of Canaan, which I give unto the children of Israel: of every tribe of their fathers shall ye send a man, every one a ruler among them.
\p
\v 3 And Moses by the commandment of the Lord sent them from the wilderness of Paran: all those men were heads of the children of Israel.
\p
\v 4 And these were their names: of the tribe of Reuben, Shammua the son of Zaccur.
\p
\v 5 Of the tribe of Simeon, Shaphat the son of Hori.
\p
\v 6 Of the tribe of Judah, - Caleb the son of Jephunneh.
\p
\v 7 Of the tribe of lssachar, Igal the son of Joseph.
\p
\v 8 Of the tribe of %phraim, Oshea the son of Nun.
\p
\v 9 Of the tribe of Benjamin, Palti the son of Raphu.
\p
\v 10 Of the tribe of Zebulun, Gaddiel the son of Sodi.
\p
\v 11 Of the tribe of Joseph, namely, of the tribe of Manasseh, Gaddi the son of Susi.
\p
\v 12 Of the tribe of Dan, Ammiel the son of Gemalli.
\p
\v 13 Of the tribe of Asher, Sethur the son of Michael.
\p
\v 14 Of the tribe of n!aphtali, Nahbi the son of Vophsi.
\p
\v 15 Of the tribe of Gad, Geuel the son of Machi.
\p
\v 16 These are the names of the men whom Moses sent to spy out the land. And Moses called Osheathe son of Nun ijoshua.
\p
\v 17 And Moses sent them to spy out the land of Canaan, and said unto them, Get you up this way southward, and go up into the mountain:
\p
\v 18 And see the land, what it is; and the people that dwelleth therein, whether they be strong or weak, few or many;
\p
\v 19 And what the land is that they dwell in, whether it be good or bad; and what cities tJiey be that they dwell in, whether in tents, or in strong holds;
\p
\v 20 And what the land is, whether it 6e fat or Mean, whether there be wood therein, or not. And be ye of good courage, and bring of the fruit of the land. Now the time was the time of the firstripe grapes.
\p
\v 21 So they went up, and searched the land from the wilderness of Zin aiito Rehob, as men come to =Hamath.
\p
\v 22 And they ascended by the south, and came unto « Hebron; where Ahiman, Sheshai, and Talmai, the children of Anak, were. (Now Hebron was built seven years before Zoan in Egypt.)
\p
\v 23 And they came unto the sbrook of Eshcol , and cut down from thence a branch with one cluster of grapes, and they bare it between two upon a staff; and they brought of the pomegranates, and of the figs.
\p
\v 24 The place was called the brook Eshcol, because of the cluster of grapes which the children of Israel cut down from thence.
\p
\v 25 And they returned from searching of the land after forty days.
\p
\v 26 And they went and came to Moses, and to Aaron, and to all the congregation of the children of Israel, unto the wilderness of Paran, to Kadesh; and brought back word unto them, and unto all the congregation, and showed them the fruit of the land.
\p
\v 27 And they told him, and said. We came unto the land whither thou sentest us, and surely it floweth with milk and honey; and this is the fruit of it.
\p
\v 28 Nevertheless the people be strong that dwell in the land, and the cities are walled, and very great: and moreover we saw the children of Anak there.
\p
\v 29 The Amalekite dwell in the land of the south: and the Hittite, and the Jebusite, and the Amorite, dwell in the mountains: and the Canaanite dwell by the sea, and by the border of Jordan.
\p
\v 30 And Caleb stilled the people before Moses, and said. Let us go up at once, and possess it; for we are well able to overcome it.
\p
\v 31 But the men that went up with him said, We are not able to go up against the people; for they are stronger than we.
\p
\v 32 And they brought up an evil report of the land which they had searched unto the children of Israel, saying. The land, through which we have gone to search it, is a land that eateth up the inhabitants thereof; and all the people that we saw in it are men of great stature.
\p
\v 33 And there we saw the giants, the sons of Anak, which come of the giants: and we were in our own sight as grasshoppers, and so we were in their sight.
\c 14
\cl CHAPTER 14
\p
\v 1 AND all the congregation lifted - up their voice, and cried; and the people wept that night.
\p
\v 2 And all the children of Israel murmured against Moses and against Aaron: and the whole congregation said unto them. Would God that we had died in the land of Egypt! or would God we had died in this wilderness !
\p
\v 3 And wherefore hath the LORD brought us unto this land, to fall by the sword, that our wives and our children should be a prey? were it not better for us to return into Egypt?
\p
\v 4 And they said one to another, Let us make a captain, and let us return into Egypt.
\p
\v 5 Then Moses and Aaron fell on their faces before all the assembly of the congregation of the children of Israel.
\p
\v 6 And Joshua the son of Nun, and 6’Caleb the son of Jephunneh, who ivere of them that searched the land, rent their clothes:
\p
\v 7 And they spake unto all the company of the children of Israel, saying. The land, which we passed through to search it, is an exceeding good land.
\p
\v 8 If the Lord delight in us, then he will bring us into this land, and give it us; a land which floweth with milk and honey.
\p
\v 9 Only not rebel ye against the Lord, neither fear ye the people of the land; for they are bread for us: their defence is departed from them, and the LORD is with us: fear them not.
\p
\v 10 But all the congregation bade stone them with stones. And the y glory of the LORD appeared in the tabernacle of the congregation before all the children of Israel.
\p
\v 11 And the LORD said unto Moses, How long will this people provoke me? and how long will it be ere they believe me, for all the -'signs which I have showed among them ?
\p
\v 12 I will smite them with the pestilence, and disinherit them, and will make of thee a greater nation and mightier than they.
\p
\v 13 And Moses said unto the Lord, Then the Egyptians shall hear it, (for thou broughtest up this people in thy might from among them;)
\p
\v 14 And they will tell it to the inhabitants of this land: or they have heard that thou LORD art among this people, that thou Lord art seen face to face, and thatthy clovid standeth over them, and that thou goest before them, by day time in a pillar of a cloud, and in a pillar of fire by night.
\p
\v 15 Now if thou Shalt kill all this people as one man, then the nations which have heard the fame of thee will speak, saying,
\p
\v 16 Because the LORD was not able to bring this people into the land which he sware unto them, therefore he hath slain them in the wilderness.
\p
\v 17 And now, I beseech thee, let the power of my Lord be great, according as thou hast spoken, saying,
\p
\v 18 The Lord z’s longsuffering, and of great mercy, forgiving iniquity and transgression, and by no means clearing the guilty, visiting the iniquity of the fathers upon the children unto the third and fourth generation.
\p
\v 19 Pardon, I beseech thee, the iniquity of this people according unto the greatness of thy mercy, and as thou hast forgiven this people, from Egypt even until now.
\p
\v 20 And the Lord said, I have pardoned according to thy word:
\p
\v 21 But as truly as I live; and as all the earth shall be filled with the glory of the LORD,
\p
\v 22 Because all those men which have seen my glory, and my miracles, which I did in Egypt and in the wilderness, and have tempted me now these ten times, and have not hearkened to my voice;
\p
\v 23 Surely they shall not see the land which I sware unto their fathers, neither shall any of them that provoked me see it;
\p
\v 24 But my servant Caleb, because he had another spirit with him, and hath followed me fully, him will I bring into the land whereinto he went; and his seed shall possess it.
\p
\v 25 (Now the Amalekites and the JCanaanites dwelt in the valley.) To morrow turn you, and get you into the wilderness by the way of the Red Sea.
\p
\v 26 And the Lord spake unto Moses and unto Aaron, saying,
\p
\v 27 How long shall I bear with this evil congregation, which murmur against me? I have heard the murmurings of the children of Israel, which they murmur against me.
\p
\v 28 Say unto them, As truly as
\p
\v 1 live, saith the LORD, as ye have spoken in mine ears, so will I do to you:
\p
\v 29 Your carcases shall fall in this wilderness; and all that were numbered of you, according to your whole number, from twenty years old and upward, who have murmured against me,
\p
\v 30 Doubtless ye shall not come into the land, concerning which I sware to make you dwell therein, save Caleb the son of Jephunneh, and - Joshua the son of Nun.
\p
\v 31 But your little ones, which ye said should be a prey, them will I bring in, and they shall know the land which ye have despised.
\p
\v 32 But as for you, your carcases, they shall fall in this wilderness.
\p
\v 33 And your children shall wander in the wilderness forty years, and bear your whoredoms, until your carcases be wasted in the wilder34 After the number of the days in which ye searched the land, even forty das, each day for a year, shall ye bear your iniquities, even forty years, and ye shall know my
\p
\v 2breach of promise.
\p
\v 35 I the Lord have said, I will surely do it unto all this evil congregation, that are gathered together against me: in this wilderness they shall be consumed, and there they shall die.
\p
\v 36 And the men, whom Moses sent to search the land, who returned, and made all the congregation to murmur against him, by bringing up a slander upon the land,
\p
\v 37 Even those men that did bring up the evil report upon the land, died by the plague before the LORD.
\p
\v 38 But Joshua the son of Nun, and Caleb the son of Jephunneh, who were of the men that went to search the land, lived still.
\p
\v 39 And Moses told these sayings unto all the children of Israel: and the people moiu-ned greatly.
\p
\v 40 And they rose up early in the morning, and gat them up into the top of the mountain, saying, Lo, we be here, and will go up unto the place which the LORD hath fpromised: for we have sinned.
\p
\v 41 And Moses said, Wherefore now do ye transgress the commandment of the Lord? but it shall not prosper.
\p
\v 42 Go not up, for the Lord is not among you; that ye be not smitten before your enemies.
\p
\v 43 For the Amalekites and the Canaanites are there before you, and ye shall fall by the sword: because ye are turned away from the Lord, therefore the Lord will not be with you.
\p
\v 44 But they presumed to go up unto the hill top: nevertheless the ark of the covenant of the Lord, and Moses, departed not out of the camp.
\p
\v 45 Then the Amalekites came down, and the Canaanites which dwelt in that hill, and smote them, and discomfited them, even unto Hormah.
\c 15
\cl CHAPTER 15
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, - saying,
\p
\v 2 Speak unto the children of Israel, and say unto them. When ye be come into the laud of your habitations, which I give unto you,
\p
\v 3 And will make an offering by fire unto the LORD, a burnt offering, or a sacrifice in performing a vow, or in a freewill offering, or in your solemn feasts, to make a sweet savour unto the Lord, of the herd, or of the flock:
\p
\v 4 Then shall he that offereth his offering unto the LORD bring a meal offering of a tenth deal of fiour mingled with the fourth part of an hin of oil.
\p
\v 5 And the fourth part of an hin of wine for a drink offering shalt thou prepare with the burnt offering or sacrifice, for one lamb.
\p
\v 6 Or for a ram, thou shalt prepare for a meal offering two tenth deals of flour mingled with the third par of an hin of oil.
\p
\v 7 And for a drink offering thou shalt offer the third part of an hin of wine, or a sweet savour unto the Lord.
\p
\v 8 And when thou preparest a bullock or a burnt offering, or for a sacrifice in performing a avow, or peace offerings unto the Lord:
\p
\v 9 Then shall he bring with a bullock a meal offering of three tenth deals of flour mingled with half an hin of oil.
\p
\v 10 And thou shalt bring for a drink offering half an hin of wine, for an offering made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the Lord.
\p
\v 11 Thus shall it be done for one bullock, or for one ram, or for a lamb, or a kid.
\p
\v 12 According to the number that ye shall prepare, so shall ye do to every one according to their number.
\p
\v 13 All that are born in the land shall do these things after this manner, in offering an offering made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the Lord.
\p
\v 14 And if a stranger sojourn with you, or whosoever be among you in your generations, and will offer an offering made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the Lord; as ye do, so he shall do.
\p
\v 15 One ordinance shall be both for you of the congregation, and also for the stranger that sojourneth with you, an ordinance for ever in your generations: as ye are, so shall the stranger be before the LORD.
\p
\v 16 One law and one custom shall be for you, and for the stranger that sojourneth with you.
\p
\v 17 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 18 Speak unto the children of Israel, and say unto them, Wh’n ye come into the Uand whither I bxing you,
\p
\v 19 Then it shall be, that, when ye eat of the bread of the land, ye shall offer up an heave offering unto the Lord.
\p
\v 20 Ye shall offer up a cake of the first of your dough for an heave offering: as ye do the heave offering of the threshingfloor, so shall ye heave it.
\p
\v 21 Of the first of your dough ye shall give unto the Lord an heave offering in your generations.
\p
\v 22 And if ye have erred, and not observed all these commandments, vyhich the LORD hath spoken unto yMoses,
\p
\v 23 Even all that the Lord hath commanded you by the hand of Moses, from the day that the Lord commanded Moses, and henceforward among your generations;
\p
\v 24 Then it shall be, if aught be committed by -'ignorance without the knowledge of the congregation, that all the congregation shall offer one young bullock for a burnt ottering, for asweetsavouruntotheLORD, with his meal offering, and his drink offering, according to the custom, and one kid of the goats for a sin offering.
\p
\v 25 And the priest shall make an atonement for all the congregation of the children of Israel, and it shall be forgiven them; for it is ignorance: and they shall bring their offering, a sacrifice made by fire unto the LORD, and their sin offering before the LORD, for their ignorance:
\p
\v 26 And it shall be forgiven all the congregation of the children of Israel, and the stranger that sojourneth among them; seeing all the people were in ignorance.
\p
\v 27 And if any soul sin through ignorance, then he shall bring a she goat of the first year for a sin offering.
\p
\v 28 And the priest shall make an atonement for the soul that sinneth ignorantly, when he sinneth by ignorance before the LORD, to make an atonement for him; and it shall be forgiven him.
\p
\v 29 Ye shall have one law for him that sinneth through ignorance, both for him that is born among the children of Israel, and for the stranger that sojourneth among them.
\p
\v 30 But the soul that doeth aught presumptuously, whether he be born in the land, or a stranger, the same reproacheth the Lord; and that soul shall be cut off from among his people.
\p
\v 31 Because he hath despised the word of the Lord, and hath broken his commandment, that soul shall utterly be cut off; his iniquity shall be upon him.
\p
\v 32 And while the children of Israel were in the wilderness, they found a man that gathered sticks upon the sabbath day.
\p
\v 33 And they that found him gathering sticks brought him unto Moses and Aaron, and unto all the congregation.
\p
\v 34 And they put him in ward, because it was not declared what should be done to him.
\p
\v 35 And the Lord said unto Moses, The man shall be surely put to death: all the congregation shall stone him with stones without the camp.
\p
\v 36 And all the congregation brought him without the camp, and stoned him with stones, and he died; as the LORD commanded Moses.
\p
\v 37 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 38 Speak unto the children of Israel, and bid them that they make them fringes in the borders of their garments throughout their generations, and that they put upon the fringe of the borders a ribband of blue:
\p
\v 39 And it shall be unto you for a fringe, that ye may look upon it, and remember all the commandments of the Lord, and do them; and that ye seek not after your own heart and your own eyes, after which ye use to go a whoring:
\p
\v 40 That ye may remember, and do all my commandments, and be holy unto your God.
\p
\v 41 I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt, to be your God: I am the Lord your God.
\c 16
\cl CHAPTER 16
\p
\v 1 NOW «Korah, the son of Izhar, the son of Kohath, the son of Levi, and Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab, and On, the son of Peleth, sons of Reuben, took men:
\p
\v 2 And they rose up before .'Moses, with certain of the children of Israel, two hundred and fifty princes of the assembly, famous in the congregation, men of renown:
\p
\v 3 And they gathered themselves together against Moses and against Aaron, and said unto them. Ye take too much upon you, seeing all the congregation are holy, every one of them, and the LORD is among them: wherefore then lift ye up yourselves above the congregation of the LORD?
\p
\v 4 And when Moses heard if, he fell upon his face:
\p
\v 5 And he spake unto Korah and unto all his company, saying, Even to morrow the LORD will show who are his, and who is holy; and will cause him to come near unto him: even him whom he hath chosen will he cause to come near unto him.
\p
\v 6 This do; Take you censers, Korah, and all his company;
\p
\v 7 And put fire therein, and put incense in them before the LORD to morrow: and it shall be that the man whom the LORD doth choose, he shall be holy: ye take too much upon you, ye sons of Levi.
\p
\v 8 And Moses said imto Korah, Hear, I pray you, ye sons of Levi:
\p
\v 9 Seemefh it 6m a small thing unto you, that the God of Israel hath separated you from the congregation of Israel, to bring you near to himself to do the service of the tabernacle of the Lord, and to stand before the congregation to minister unto them?
\p
\v 10 And he hath brought thee near to him, and all thy brethren the sons of Levi with thee: and seek ye the priesthood also?
\p
\v 11 For which cause both thou and all thy company are gathered together against the LORD: and what IS Aaron, that ye murmur against him?
\p
\v 12 And Moses sent to call Dathan and Abiram, the sons of Eliab: who said, We will not come up:
\p
\v 13 Is it a small thing that thou hast brought us up out of a Hand that floweth with milk and honey, to kill us in the wilderness, except thou make thyself altogether a prince over us?
\p
\v 14 Moreover thou hast not brought us into a land that floweth with milk and honey, or given us inheritance of fields and vineyards: wilt thou put out the eyes of these men? we will not come up.
\p
\v 15 And Moses was very wroth, and said unto the LORD, Respect not thou their offering: I have not taken one ass from them, neither have I hurt one of them.
\p
\v 16 And Moses said unto Korah, Be thou and all thy company before the Lord, thou, and they, and Aaron, to morrow:
\p
\v 17 And take every man his censer, | and put incense in them, and bring ye before the LORD every man his censer, two hundred and fifty censers; thou also, and Aaron, each of you his censer.
\p
\v 18 And they took every man his censer, and put fire in them, and laid incense thereon, and stood in the door of the 2tabernacle of the congregation with Moses and Aaron.
\p
\v 19 And Korah gathered all the congregation against them unto the door of the tabernacle of the congregation: and the glory of the Lord appeared unto all the congregation.
\p
\v 20 And the Lord spake unto Moses and unto Aaron, saying,
\p
\v 21 Separate yourselves from among this congregation, that I may consume them in a moment.
\p
\v 22 And they fell upon their faces, and said, O God, the God of the Spirits of all flesh, shall one man sin, and wilt thou be wroth with ali the congregation ?
\p
\v 23 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 24 Speak unto the congregation, saying, Get you up from about the tabernacle of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram.
\p
\v 25 And Moses rose up and went unto Dathan and Abiram; and the elders of Israel followed him.
\p
\v 26 And he spake unto the congregation, saying. Depart, I pray you, from the tents of these wicked men, and touch nothing of theirs, lest ye be consumed in all their sins.
\p
\v 27 So they gat up from the tabernacle of J Korah, Dathan, and Abiram, on every side: and Dathan and Abiram came out, and stood in the door of their tents, and their wives, and their sons, and their little children.
\p
\v 28 And Moses said, Hereby ye shall know that the LORD hath sent me to do all these works; for I have not done them of mine own mind.
\p
\v 29 If these men die the common death of all men, or if they be visited after the visitation of all men; theii the Lord hath not sent me.
\p
\v 30 But if the Lord make a new thing, and the earth open her mouth, and swallow them up, with all that appertain unto them, and they go down living into the spit; then ye shall understand that these men have provoked the LORD.
\p
\v 31 And it came to pass, as he had made an end of speaking all these words, that the ground clave asunder that was under them:
\p
\v 32 And the earth opened her mouth, and swallowed them up, and their houses, and all the men that appertained unto Korah, and all their goods.
\p
\v 33 They, and all that appertained to them, went down alive into the pit, and the earth closed upon them: and they perished from among the congregation.
\p
\v 34 And all Israel that were round about them fled at the cry of them: for they said, Lest the earth swallow us up also.
\p
\v 35 And there came out a fire from the Lord, and consumed the two hundred and fifty men that offered incense.
\p
\v 36 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 37 Speak unto Eleazarthe son of Aaron the priest, that he take up the censers out of the burning, and scatter thou the fire yonder; for they are hallowed.
\p
\v 38 The censers of these sinners against their own souls, let them make them broad plates for a covering of the altar: for they offered them before the LORD, therefore they are hallowed: and they shall be a sign unto the children of Israel.
\p
\v 39 And Eleazar the priest took the ybrasen censers, wherewith they that were burnt had offered; and they were made broad plates for a covering of the altar:
\p
\v 40 To he a § memorial unto the children of Israel, that no stranger, that is not of the seed of Aaron, come near to offer incense before the Lord; that he be not as Korah, and as his company: as the LORD said to him by the hand of Moses.
\p
\v 41 But on the morrow all the congregation of the children of Israel murmured against Moses and against Aaron, saying, Ye have killed the people of the LORD.
\p
\v 42 And it came to pass, when the congregation was gathered against Moses and against Aaron, that they looked toward the tabernacle of the congregation: and, behold, the cloud covered it, and the glory of the Lord appeared.
\p
\v 43 And Moses and Aaron came before the tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 44 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 45 Get you up from among this congregation, that I may consume them as in a moment. And they fell upon their faces.
\p
\v 46 And Moses said unto Aaron, Take a censer, and put fire therein from off the altar, and put on incense, and go -'quickly unto the congregation, and make an atonement for them: for there is wrath gone out from the LORD; the -'plague is begun,
\p
\v 47 And Aaron took as Moses commanded, and ran into the midst of the congregation; and, behold, the plague was begun among the people: and he put on incense, and made an atonement for the people.
\p
\v 48 And he stood between the dead and the living; and the plague was stayed.
\p
\v 49 Now they that died in the plague were fourteen thousand and seven hundred, beside them that died about the matter of Korah.
\p
\v 50 And Aaron returned unto Moses unto the door of the tabernacle of the congregation: and the plague was stayed.
\c 17
\cl CHAPTER 17
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 2 Speak unto the children of Israel, and take of every one of them a rod according to the house of their fathers, of all their princes according to the house of their fathers twelve rods: write thou every man’s name upon his rod.
\p
\v 3 And thou shalt write Aaron’s name upon the rod of Levi: for one rod shall be for the head of the house of their fathers.
\p
\v 4 And thou shalt lay them up in the itabernacle of the congregation before the testimony, where I will meet with you.
\p
\v 5 And it shall come to pass, that the man’s rod, whom I shall choose, shall blossom: and I will make to cease from me the murmurings of the children of Israel, whereby they murmur against you.
\p
\v 6 And Moses spake unto the children of Israel, and every one of their princes gave him a rod apiece, for each prince one, according to their fathers' houses, even twelve rods: and the rod of Aaron was among their rods.
\p
\v 7 And Moses laid up the rods before the Lord in the tabernacle of witness.
\p
\v 8 And it came to pass, that on the morrow Moses went into the tabernacle of witness; and, behold, the rod of Aaron for the house of Levi was budded, and brought forth buds, and bloomed blossoms, and yielded almonds.
\p
\v 9 And Moses brought out all the rods from before the LORD unto all the children of Israel: and they looked, and took every man his rod.
\p
\v 10 And the LORD said unto Moses, Bring Aaron’s rod again before the testimony, to be kept for a token against the rebels; and thou shalt quite take away their .ftourmurings from me, that they die not.
\p
\v 11 And Moses did so: as the LORD commanded him, so did he.
\p
\v 12 And the children of Israel spake unto Moses, saying, Behold, we die, we perish, we all perish.
\p
\v 13 Whosoever cometh any thing near unto the 2 tabernacle of the Lord shall die: shall we all be consumed with dying?
\c 18
\cl CHAPTER 18
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord said unto «Aaron, - Thou and thy sons and thy father’s house with thee shall bear the iniquity of the sanctuary: and thou and thy sons with thee shall bear the iniquity of your priesthood.
\p
\v 2 And thy brethren also of the tribe of Levi, the tribe of thy father, bring thou with thee, that they may be joined unto thee, and minister unto thee: but thou and thy sons with thee shall minister before the itabernacle of witness.
\p
\v 3 And they shall keep thy charge, and the charge of all the tabernacle: only they shall not come nigh the vessels of the sanctuary and the altar, that neither they, nor ye also, die.
\p
\v 4 And they shall be joined unto thee, and keep the charge of the tabernacle of the congregation, for all the service of the tabernacle: and a stranger shall not come nigh unto you.
\p
\v 5 And ye shall keep the charge of the sanctuary, and the charge of the altar: that there be no wrath any more upon the children of Israel.
\p
\v 6 And I, behold, I have taken your brethren the Levites from among the children of Israel: to you they are given as a gift for the Lord, to do the service of the tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 7 Therefore thou and thy sons with thee shall keep your priest’s office for every thing of the altar, and within the vail; and ye shall serve: I have given your priest’s office unto you as a service of gift: and the stranger that cometh nigh shall be put to death.
\p
\v 8 And the LORD spake unto Aaron, Behold, I also have given thee the charge of mine heave oiferings of all the hallowed things of the children of Israel; unto thee have I given them by reason of the anointing, and to thy sons, by an ordinance for ever.
\p
\v 9 This shall be thine of the most holy things, reserved from the fire: every oblation of theirs, every meal offering of theirs, and every sin offering of theirs, and every trespass offering of theirs, which they shall render unto me, shall be most holy for thee and for thy sons.
\p
\v 10 In the most holy place shalt thou eat it; every male shall eat it: it shall be holy unto thee.
\p
\v 11 And this is thine; the heave offering of their gift, with all the wave offerings of the children of Israel: I have given them unto thee, and to thy sons and to thy daughters with thee, by a statute for ever: every one that is clean in thy house shall eat of it.
\p
\v 12 All the best of the oil, and all the best of the wine, and of the wheat, the .firstfruits of them which they shall offer unto the LORD, them have I given thee.
\p
\v 13 And whatsoever is first ripe in the land, which they shall bring unto the LORD, shall be thine; every one that is clean in thine house shall eat of it.
\p
\v 14 Every thing sdevoted in Israel shall be thine.
\p
\v 15 Every thing that openeth the womb in all flesh, which they bring unto the LORD, whether it be of men or beasts, shall be thine: nevertheless the firstborn of man shalt thou surely redeem, and the firstling of unclean beasts shalt thou redeem.
\p
\v 16 And those that are to be redeemed from a month old shall thou redeem, according to thine estimation, for the money of five -'shekels, after the shekel of the sanctuary, which is twenty gerahs.
\p
\v 17 But the firstling of a cow, or the firstling of a sheep, or the firstling of a goat, thou shalt not redeem; they are holy: thou shalt sprinkle their blood upon the altar, and shalt burn their fat for an offering made by fire, for a sv,7eet savour unto the Lord.
\p
\v 18 And the flesh of them shall be thine, as the wave breast and as the right shoulder are thine.
\p
\v 19 All the heave offerings of the holy things, which the children of Israel offer unto the LORD, have I given thee, and thy sons and thy daughters with thee, by a statute for ever: it is a covenant of -'salt for ever before the LORD unto thee and to thy seed with thee.
\p
\v 20 And the LORD spake unto Aaron, Thou shalt have no inheritance in their land, neither shalt thou have any part among them: I am thy part and thine inheritance among the children of Israel.
\p
\v 21 And, behold, I have given the children of Levi all the tenth in Israel for an inheritance, for their service which they serve, even the service of the tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 22 Neither must the children of Israel henceforth come nih the tabernacle of the congregation, lest they bear sin, and die.
\p
\v 23 But the Levites shall do the service of the tabernacle of the congregation, and they shall bear their iniquity: if shall be a statute for ever throughout your generations, that among the children of Israel they have no inheritance.
\p
\v 24 But the tithes of the children of Israel, which they offer as an heave offering unto the LORD, I have given to the Levites to inherit: therefore I have said unto them. Among the children of Israel they shall have no inheritance.
\p
\v 25 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 26 Thus speak unto the Levites, and say unto them, When ye take of the children of Israel the tithes which I have given you from them for your inheritance, then ye shall offer up an heave offering of it for the Lord, even a tenth pai’t of the tithe.
\p
\v 27 And this your heave offering shall be reckoned unto you, as though it were the corn of the threshingfloor, and as the fulness of the winepress.
\p
\v 28 Thus ye also shall offer an heave offering unto the LORD of all your tithes, which ye receive of the children of Israel; and ye shall give thereof the Lord’s heave offering to Aaron the priest.
\p
\v 29 Out of all your gifts ye shall offer every heave offering of the Lord, of all the best thereof, even the hallowed part thereof out of it.
\p
\v 30 Therefore thou shalt say unto them. When ye have heaved the best thereof from it, then it shall be counted unto the Levites as the increase of the threshingfloor, and as the increase of the winepress.
\p
\v 31 And ye shall eat it in every place, ye and your households: for it is your reward for your service in the tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 32 And ye shall bear no sin by reason of it, when ye have heaved from it the best of it: neither shall ye pollute the holy things of the children of Israel, lest ye die.
\c 19
\cl CHAPTER 19
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses . and unto Aaron, saying,
\p
\v 2 This is the ordinance of the law which the Lord hath commanded, saying. Speak unto the children of Israel, that they bring thee a red heifer without spot, wherein is no blemish, and upon vrhich never came yoke:
\p
\v 3 And ye shall give it unto Eleazar the priest, that he may bring it forth without the camp, and one shall slay it before his face:
\p
\v 4 And Eleazar the priest shall take of its blood with his finger, and sprinkle of its blood directly before the itabernacle of the congregation seven times:
\p
\v 5 And one shall burn the heifer in his sight; its skin, and its flesh, and its blood, with its dung, shall he burn:
\p
\v 6 And the priest shall take cedar wood, and hyssop, and i’scarlet, and cast it into the midst of the burning of the heifer.
\p
\v 7 Then the priest shall wash his clothes, and he shall bathe his flesh in water, and afterward he shall come into the camp, and the priest shall be unclean until the even.
\p
\v 8 And he that burneth it shall wash his clothes in water, and bathe his flesh in water, and shall be unclean until the even.
\p
\v 9 And a man that is clean shall gather up the ashes of the heifer, and lay them up without the camp in a clean place, and it shall be kept for the congregation of the children of Israel for a water of separation: it is a purification for sin.
\p
\v 10 And he that gathereth the ashes of the heifer shall wash his clothes, and be unclean until the even: and it shall be unto the children of Israel, and unto the stranger that sojourneth among them, for a statute for ever.
\p
\v 11 He that toucheth the dead body of any man shall be unclean seven days.
\p
\v 12 He shall spurify himself with it on the third day, and on the seventh day he shall be clean: but if he purify not himself the third day, then the seventh day he shall not be clean.
\p
\v 13 Whosoever toucheth the dead body of any man that is dead, and purifieth not himself, defileth the tabernacle of the Lord; and that soul shall be cut off from Israel: because the water of separation was not sprinkled upon him, he shall be unclean; his uncleanness is yet upon him.
\p
\v 14 This is the law, when a man dieth in a tent: all that come into the tent, and all that is in the tent, shall be unclean seven days.
\p
\v 15 And every open vessel, which hath no covering bound upon it, is unclean.
\p
\v 16 And whosoever toucheth one that is slain with a sword in the open fields, or a dead body, or a bone of a man, or a grave, shall be unclean seven days.
\p
\v 17 And for an unclean person they shall take of the ashes of the burnt heifer of purification for sin, and running water shall be put thereto in a vessel:
\p
\v 18 And a clean person shall take hyssop, and dip it in the water, and sprinkle it upon the tent, and upon all the vessels, and upon the persons that were there, and upon him that touched a bone, or one slain, or one dead, or a grave:
\p
\v 19 And the clean person shall sprinkle upon the unclean on the third day, and on the seventh day: and on the seventh day he shall purify himself, and wash his clothes, and bathe himself in water, and shall be clean at even.
\p
\v 20 But the man that shall be unclean, and shall not purify himself, that soul shall be cut off from among the congregation, because he hath defiled the sanctuary of the LORD: the water of separation hath not been sprinkled upon him; he is unclean.
\p
\v 21 And it shall be a perpetual statute unto them, that he that sprinkleth the water of separation shall wash his clothes; and he that toucheth the water of separation shall be unclean until even.
\p
\v 22 And whatsoever the unclean person toucheth shall be unclean; and the soul that toucheth it shall be unclean until even.
\c 20
\cl CHAPTER 20
\p
\v 1 THEN came the children of Israel, even the whole congregation, into the desert of Zin in the
\p
\v 2first month: and the people abode in Kadesh; and Miriam died there, and was buried there.
\p
\v 2 And there was no water for the congregation: and they gathered themselves together against Moses and against Aaron.,
\p
\v 3 And the people quarrelled with Moses, and spake, saying, Would God that we had died when our brethren died before the Lord !
\p
\v 4 And why have ye brought up the congregation of the LORD into this wilderness, that we and our cattle should die there?
\p
\v 5 And wherefore have ye made us to come lip out of .'Egypt, to bring us in unto this evil place? it is no place of seed, or of figs, or of vines, or of pomegranates; neither is there any water to drink.
\p
\v 6 And Moses and Aaron went from the presence of the assembly unto the door of the tabernacle of the congregation, and they fell upon their faces: and the glory of the Lord appeared unto them.
\p
\v 7 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 8 Take the rod, and gather thou the assembly together, thou, and Aaron thy brother, and speak ye unto the rock before their -'eyes; and it shall give forth its water, and thou shalt bring forth to them water out of the rock: so thou shalt give the congregation and their beasts drink
\p
\v 9 And Moses took the rod from before the Lord, as he commanded him.
\p
\v 10 And Moses and Aaron gathered the congregation together before the rock, and he said unto them. Hear now, ye rebels; must we fetch you water out of this rock?
\p
\v 11 And Moses lifted up his hand, and with his rod he smote the rock twice: and the water came out abundantly, and the congregation drank, and their beasts also.
\p
\v 12 And the LORD spake unto Moses and Aaron, Because ye believed me not, to sanctify me in the eyes of the children of Israel, therefore ye shall not bring this congregation into the land which I have given them.
\p
\v 13 This is the water of Meribah: because the children of Israel strove with the Lord, and he was sanctified in them.
\p
\v 14 And Mosessentmessengers from Kadesh unto the kingofEdom, Thus saith thy brother Israel, Thou knowest all the hardships that have befallen us:
\p
\v 15 How our fathers went down into Egypt, and we have dwelt in Egypt along time; and the ! Egyptians vexed us, and our fathers:
\p
\v 16 And when we cried unto the LORD, he heard our voice, and sent an angel, and hath brought us forth out of Egypt: and, hehold, we are in Kadesh, a city in the uttermost of thy border:
\p
\v 17 Let us pass, I pray thee, through thy country: we will not pass through the fields, or through the vineyards, neither will we drink of the water of the wells: we will go by the king’s high way, we will not turn to the right hand nor to the left, until we have passed thy borders.
\p
\v 18 And Edom said unto him. Thou shalt not pass by me, lest I come out against thee with the sword.
\p
\v 19 And the children of Israel said unto him. We will go by the high way: and if I and my cattle drink of thy water, then I will pay for it: I will only, without doing any thing e?se, go through on my feet.
\p
\v 20 And he said, Thou shalt not go through. And Edom came out against him with much people, and with a strong hand.
\p
\v 21 Thus Edom refused to give Israel passage through his border: wherefore Israel turned away from him.
\p
\v 22 And the children of Israel, even the whole congregation, journeyed from Kadesh, and came unto mount Hor.
\p
\v 23 And the Lord spake unto Moses and Aaron in mount Hor, by the coast of the land of Edom, saying,
\p
\v 24 Aaron shall be gathered unto his people: for he shall not enter into the land which I have given unto the children of Israel, because ye rebelled against my word at the water of Meribah.
\p
\v 25 Take Aaron and Eleazar his son, and bring them up unto mount Hor:
\p
\v 26 And strip Aaron of his garments, and put them upon Eleazar his son: and Aaron shall be gathered iinto his people, and shall die there.
\p
\v 27 And Moses did as the LORD commanded: and tYiQy went up into mount Hor in the sight of all the congregation.
\p
\v 28 And Moses stripped Aaron of his garments, and put them upon Eleazar his son; and Aaron died there in the top of tlie mount: and Moses and Eleazar came down from the mount.
\p
\v 29 And when all the congregation saw that Aaron was dead, they mourned for Aaron thirty days, even all the house of Israel.
\c 21
\cl CHAPTER 21
\p
\v 1 AND when king «=Arad the Ca- naanite, who dwelt in the south, heard tell that Israel came by the way of the spies; then he fought against Israel, and took some of them prisoners.
\p
\v 2 And Israel vowed a vow unto the Lord, and said. If thou wilt indeed deliver this people into my hand, then I will utterly destroy their cities.
\p
\v 3 And the LORD hearkened to the voice of Israel, and delivered up the Canaa.nites; and they utterly destroyed them and their cities: and he called the name of the place Hormah.
\p
\v 4 And they journeyed from mount Hor by the way of the Red Sea, to compass the .'iand of Edom: and the soul of the people was much discouraged because of the way.
\p
\v 5 And the people spake against God, and against Moses, Wherefore have ye brought us up out of jEgypt to die in the wilderness? for there is no bread, neither is there any water; and our soul loatheth this light bread.
\p
\v 6 And the Lord sent fiery serpents among the people, and they bit the people; and much people of Israel died.
\p
\v 7 Therefore the people came to Moses, and said. We have sinned, for we have spoken against the Lord, and against thee; pray unto the Lord, that he take away the serpents from us. And Moses prayed for the people.
\p
\v 8 And the LORD said unto Moses, Make thee a fiery serpent, and set it upon a pole: and it shall come to pass, that every one that is bitten, when he looketh upon it, shall live.
\p
\v 9 And Moses made a serpent of brass, and put it upon a pole, and it came to pass, that if a serpent had bitten any man, when he beheld the serpent of brass, he lived.
\p
\v 10 And the children of Israel set forward, and pitched in Oboth.
\p
\v 11 And they journeyed from Oboth, and pitched at Ije-abarim, in the wilderness which is before Moab, toward the sunrising.
\p
\v 12 From thence they removed, and pitched in the valley of Zared.
\p
\v 13 From thence they removed, and pitched on the other side of Amon, which is in the wilderness that Cometh out of the coasts of the Amorites: for Arnon is the border of Moab, between Moab and the Amorites.
\p
\v 14 Wherefore it is said in the book of the wars of the Lord, What he did in the Red Sea, and in the brooks of Arnon,
\p
\v 15 And at the stream of the brooks that goeth down to the dwelling of Ar, and lieth upon the border of Moab.
\p
\v 16 And from thence they went to Beer: that is the well whereof the Lord spake unto Moses, Gather the people together, and I will give them water.
\p
\v 17 Then Israel sang this song, Spring up, O well; sing ye unto it:
\p
\v 18 The princes digged the well, the nobles of the people digged it, by the direction of the lawgiver, with their staves. And from the wilderness they went to Mattanah:
\p
\v 19 And from Mattanah to Nahaliel: and from Nahaliel to Bamoth:
\p
\v 20 And from Bamoth in the valley, that is in the country of Moab, to the top of Pisgah, which looketh toward Jeshimon.
\p
\v 21 And Israel sent messengers unto Sihon king of the Amorites, saying,
\p
\v 22 Let me pass through thy land: we will not turn into the fields, or into the vineyards; we will not drink of the waters of the well: but we will go along by the king’s high way, until we have passed thy borders.
\p
\v 23 And Sihon would not suffer Israel to pass through his border: but Sihon gathered all his people together, and went out against Israel into the wilderness: and he came to Jahaz, and fought against Israel.
\p
\v 24 And Israel smote him with the edge of the sword, and possessed his land from Arnon unto Jabbok, even unto the children of Ammon: for the border of the children of Ammon was strong.
\p
\v 25 And Israel took all these cities: and Israel dwelt in all the cities of the Amorites, in Heshbon, and in all the villages thereof.
\p
\v 26 For .Heshbon was the city of Sihon the king of the Amorites, who had fought against the former king of Moab, and taken all his land out of his hand, even unto Arnon.
\p
\v 27 Wherefore they that speak in yproverbs say, Come into Heshbon, let the city of Sihon be built and prepared:
\p
\v 28 For there is a fire gone out of Heshbon, a flame from the city of Sihon: it hath consumed Ar of Moab, and the lords of the high places of Arnon.
\p
\v 29 Woe to thee, Moab! thou art undone, O people of Chemosh: he hath given his sons that escaped, and his daughters, into captivity unto Sihon king of the Amorites.
\p
\v 30 We have shot at them; Heshbon is perished even unto Dibon, and we have laid them waste even unto Nophah, which reacheth unto Medeba.
\p
\v 31 Thus Israel dwelt in the land of the Amorites.
\p
\v 32 And Moses sent to spy out Jaazer, and they took the villages thereof, and drove out the Amorites that were there.
\p
\v 33 And they turned and went up by the way of Bashan: and Og the king of Bashan went out against them, he, and all his people, to the battle at Edrei.
\p
\v 34 And the LORD said unto Moses, Fear him not: for I have delivered him into thy hand, and all his people, and his land; and thou shalt do to him as thou didst unto Sihon king of the Amorites, which dwelt at Heshbon.
\p
\v 35 So they smote him, and his sons, and all his people, until there was none left him alive; and they possessed his land.
\c 22
\cl CHAPTER 22
\p
\v 1 AND the children of Israel set for- ward, and pitched in the plains of Moab on this side Jordan by Jericho.
\p
\v 2 And Balak the son of «Zippor saw all that Israel had done to the Amorites.
\p
\v 3 And Moab was sore afraid of the people, because they were many: and Moab was distressed because of the children of Israel.
\p
\v 4 And Moab said unto the elders of Midian, Now shall this company lick up all that are round about us, as the ox licketh up the grass of the field. And .?Balak the son of Zipper was king of the Moabites at that time.
\p
\v 5 He sent messengers therefore unto Balaam the son of Beor to yPethor, which is by the river of the land of the children of his people, to call him, saying, Behold, there is a people come out from -'Egypt: behold, they cover the face of the earth, and they abide over against me:
\p
\v 6 Come now therefore, I pray thee, curse me this people; for they are too mighty for me: peradventure I shall prevail, that we may smite them, and that I may drive them out of the land: for I observe that he whom, thou blessest is blessed, and he whom thou cursest is cursed.
\p
\v 7 And the elders of Moab and the elders of Midian departed with the rewards of divination in their hand; and they came unto Balaam, and spake unto him the words of Balak.
\p
\v 8 And he said unto them. Lodge here this night, and I will bring you word again, as the LORD shall speak unto me: and the princes of Moab abode with Balaam.
\p
\v 9 And God came unto Balaam, and said. What men are these with thee?
\p
\v 10 And Balaam said unto God, Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab, hath sent unto me, saying,
\p
\v 11 Behold, there is a people come out of Egypt, which covereth the face of the earth: come now, curse me them; peradventure I shall be able to overcome them, and drive them out.
\p
\v 12 And God said unto Balaam, Thou Shalt not go with them; thou Shalt not curse the people: for they are blessed.
\p
\v 13 And Balaam rose up in the morning, and said unto the princes of Balak, Get you into your land: for the Lord refuseth to give me leave to go with you.
\p
\v 14 And the princes of Moab rose up, and they went unto Balak, and said, Balaam refuseth to come with us.
\p
\v 15 And Balak sent yet again princes, more, and more honourable than they.
\p
\v 16 And they came to Balaam, and said to him, Thus saith Balak the son of Zippor, Let nothing, I pray thee, hinder thee from coming unto me:
\p
\v 17 For I will promote thee unto very great honour, and I will do whatsoever thou sayest unto me: come therefore, I pray thee, curse me this people.
\p
\v 18 And Balaam answered and said unto the servants of Balak, If Balak would give me his house full of silver and gold, I cannot go beyond the word of the LORD my God, to do less or more.
\p
\v 19 Now therefore, I pray you, tarry ye also here this night, that I may know what the Lord vill say unto me more.
\p
\v 20 And God came unto Balaam at night, and said unto him. If the men come to call thee, rise up, and go with them; but yet the word which I shall say unto thee, that Shalt thou do.
\p
\v 21 And Balaam rose up in the morning, and saddled his ass, and went with the princes of Moab.
\p
\v 22 And God’s anger was kindled because he went: and the angel of the Lord stood in the way for an adversary against him. Now he was riding upon his ass, and his two servants were with him.
\p
\v 23 And the ass saw the angel of the Lord standing in the way, and his sword drawn in his hand: and the ass turned aside out of the vray, and went into the field: and Balaam smote the ass, to turn her into the way.
\p
\v 24 But the angel of the LORD stood in a path of the vineyards, a wall being on this side, and a wall on that side.
\p
\v 25 And when the ass saw the angel of the Lord, she thrust herself unto the wall, and crushed Balaam’s foot against the wall: and he smote her again.
\p
\v 26 And the angel of the LORD went further, and stood in a narrow place, where was no way to turn either to the right hand or to the left.
\p
\v 27 And when the ass saw the angel of the Lord, she fell down under Balaam: and Balaam’s anger was kindled, and he smote the ass with a staff.
\p
\v 28 And the LORD opened the mouth of the ass, and she said unto Balaam, What have I done unto thee, that thou hast smitten me these three times?
\p
\v 29 And Balaam said unto the ass. Because thou hast mocked me: I would there were a sword in mine hand, for now would I kill thee.
\p
\v 30 And the ass said unto Balaam, Am not I thine ass, upon which thou hast ridden ever since I was thine unto this day? was I ever wont to do so unto thee? And he said. Nay.
\p
\v 31 Then the LORD J opened the eyes of Balaam, and he saw the angel of the Lord standing in the way, and his sword drawn in his hand: and he bowed down his head, and fell flat on his face.
\p
\v 32 And the angel of the LORD said unto him, Wherefore hast thou smitten thine ass these three times? behold, I went out to withstand thee, because thy way is perverse before me:
\p
\v 33 And the ass saw me, and turned from me these three times: unless she had turned from me, surely now also I had slain thee, and saved her alive.
\p
\v 34 And Balaam said unto the angel of the Lord, I have sinned; for I knew not that thou stoodest in the way against me: now therefore, if it displease thee, I will get me back again.
\p
\v 35 And the angel of the LORD said unto Balaam, Go with the men: but only the word that I shall speak unto thee, that thou shalt speak. So Balaam went with the princes of Balak.
\p
\v 36 And when Balak heard that Balaam was come, he went out to meet him unto a city of Moab, which is in the border of Arnon, which is in the utmost coast.
\p
\v 37 And Balak said unto Balaam, Did I not earnestly send unto thee to call thee? wherefore caniest thou not unto me? am I not able indeed to promote thee to honour?
\p
\v 38 And Balaam said unto Balak, Lo, I am come unto thee: have I now any power at all to say any thing? the word that God putteth in my mouth, that shall I speak.
\p
\v 39 And Balaam went with Balak, and they came unto Kirjath-huzoth.
\p
\v 40 And Balak offered oxen and sheep, and sent to Balaam, and to the princes that were with him.
\p
\v 41 And it came to pass on the morrow, that Balak took Balaam, and brought him up into the high places of Baal, that thence he might see the utmost part of the people.
\c 23
\cl CHAPTER 23
\p
\v 1 AND Balaam said unto Balak, - Build me here seven altars, and prepare me here seven oxen and seven rams.
\p
\v 2 And Balak did as Balaam had spoken; and Balak and Balaam offered on every altar a bullock and a ram.
\p
\v 3 And Balaam said unto Balak, Stand by thy burnt offering, and I will go: peradventure the LORD will come to meet me: and whatsoever he showeth me I will tell thee, he went to an high place.
\p
\v 4 And God met Balaam: and he said unto him, I have prepared seven altars, and I have offered upon every altarta bullock and a ram.
\p
\v 5 And the LORD put a word in Balaam’s mouth, and said. Return unto Balak, and thus thou shalt speak.
\p
\v 6 And he returned unto him, and, lo, he stood by his burnt sacrifice, he, and all the princes of Moab.
\p
\v 7 And he took up his sparable, and said, Balak the king of Moab hath brought me from Aram, out of the mountains of the east, saying, Come, curse me Jacob, and come, defy Israel.
\p
\v 8 How shall I curse, whom God hath not cursed ? or how shall I defy, whom the LORD hath not defied?
\p
\v 9 For from the top of the rocks I see him, and from the hills I behold him: lo, the people shall dwell alone, and shall not be reckoned among the nations.
\p
\v 10 Who can count the dust of Jacob, and the number of the fourth part of Israel? Let me die the death of the righteous, and let my last end be like his!
\p
\v 11 And Balak said unto Balaam, What hast [thou done unto me? I took thee to curse mine enemies, and, behold, thou hast blessed them altogether.
\p
\v 12 And he answered and said. Must I not take heed to speak that which the Lord hath put in my mouth?
\p
\v 13 And Balak said unto him, Come, I pray thee, with me unto another place, from whence thou mayest see them: thou shalt see but the utmost part of them, and shalt not see them all: and curse me them from thence.
\p
\v 14 And he brought him into the field of Zophim, to the top of iTisgah, and built seven altars, and offered a bullock and a ram on every altar.
\p
\v 15 And he said unto Balak, Stand here by the burnt offering, while I meet the LORD yonder.
\p
\v 16 And the LORD met Balaam, and put a word in his mouth, and said, Go again unto Balak, and say thus.
\p
\v 17 And when he came to him, behold, he stood by his burnt offering, and the princes of Moab with him. And Balak said unto him, What hath the LORD spoken ?
\p
\v 18 And he took up his parable, and said, Rise up, Balak, and hear; hearken unto me, thou son of Zippor:
\p
\v 19 God is not a man, that he should lie; neither the son of man, that he should repent: hath he said, and shall he not do it? or hath he spoken, and shall he not make it good ?
\p
\v 20 Behold, I have received commandment to bless: and he hath blessed; and I cannot reverse it.
\p
\v 21 He hath not beheld iniquity in Jacob, neither hath he seen perverseness in Israel: the LORD his God is with him, and the shout of a king is among them.
\p
\v 22 God brought them out of Egypt; he hath as it were the strength ol a vild ox.
\p
\v 23 Surely there is no enchantment against j-cob, neither is there any divination against Israel: according to this time it shall be said of Jacob and of Israel, What hath God wrought !
\p
\v 24 Behold, the people shall rise up as a great lion, and lift up himself as a young lion: he shall not lie down until he eat of the prey, and j drink the blood of the slain.
\p
\v 25 And Balak said untoBalaam, Neither curse them at all, nor bless them at all.
\p
\v 26 But Balaam answered and said unto Balak, Told not I thee, saying, All that the LORD speaketh, that I must do ?
\p
\v 27 And Balak said unto Balaam, Come, I pray thee, I will bring thee unto another place; peradventure it will please God that thou may est curse me them from thence.
\p
\v 28 And Balak brought Balaam unto the top of Peor, that looketh | toward Jeshimon. j
\p
\v 29 And Balaam said unto Balak, j Build me here seven altars, and prepare me here seven bullocks and seven rams. !
\p
\v 30 And Balak did as Balaam had I said, and offered a bullock and a ram on every altar.
\c 24
\cl CHAPTER 24
\p
\v 1 AND when Balaam saw that it tl. pleased the LORD to bless Israel, he went not, as at other times, to seek for enchantments, but he set his face toward the wilderness.
\p
\v 2 And Balaam lifted up his «eyes, and he saw Israel abiding in his tents according to their tribes; and the spirit of God came upon him.
\p
\v 3 And he took up his parable, and said, Balaam the son of Beor hath said, and the man whose eyes are open hath said:
\p
\v 4 He hath said, who heard the words of God, who saw the vision of the Almighty, falling into a trance, but having his eyes open:
\p
\v 5 How goodly are thy tents, O Jacob, and thy ifabernacles, O Israel!
\p
\v 6 As the valleys are they spread forth, as gardens by the river’s side, as the trees of lign aloes which the Lord hath planted, and as cedar trees beside the waters.
\p
\v 7 He shall pour the water out of his buckets, and his seed shall be in many waters, and his king shall be higher than 6A.gag, and his kingdom shall be exalted.
\p
\v 8 God brought him forth out of Egypt; he hath as it were the strength of a wild ox: he shall eat up the nations his enemies, and shall break their bones, and pierce them through with his arrows.
\p
\v 9 He couched, he lay down as a lion, and as a great lion: who shall stir him up? Blessed is he that blesseth thee, and cursed is he that curseth thee.
\p
\v 10 And Balak’s anger was kindled against Balaam, and he smote his hands together: and Balak said unto Balaam, I called thee to curse mine enemies, and, behold, thou hast altogether blessed them these three times.
\p
\v 11 Therefore now flee thou to thy place: I thought to promote thee unto great honour; but, lo, the LORD hath kept thee back from honour.
\p
\v 12 And Balaam said unto Balak, Spake I not also to thy messengers which thou sentest unto me, saying,
\p
\v 13 If Balak would give me his house full of silver and gold, I cannot go beyond the commandment of the Lord, to do either good or bad of mine own mind; but what the Lord saith, that will I speak ?
\p
\v 14 And now, behold, I go unto my people: come therefore, and I will advertise thee what this people shall do to thy people in the latter days.
\p
\v 15 And he took up his parable, and said, Balaam the son of Beor hath said, and the man whose eyes are open hath said:
\p
\v 16 He hath said, who heard the words of God, and knew the knowledge of the most High, who saw the vision of the Almighty, falling into a trance, but having his eyes open:
\p
\v 17 I shall see him, but not now: I shall behold him, but not nigh: there shall come a Star out of Jacob, and a Sceptre shall rise out of Israel, and shall smite the corners of Moab, and destroy all the children of Sheth.
\p
\v 18 And Edom shall be a possession, Seir also shall be a possession for his enemies; and Israel shall do valiantly.
\p
\v 19 Out of Jacob shall come he that shall have !? dominion, and shall destroy him that remaineth of the city.
\p
\v 20 And when he looked on =''Amalek, he took up his Sparable, and said, Amalek was the first of the nations; but his latter end shall be that he perish for ever.
\p
\v 21 And he looked on the Kenites, and took up his parable, and said. Strong is thy dwellingplace, and thou puttest thy nest in a rock.
\p
\v 22 Nevertheless the Kenite shall be wasted, until Asshur shall carry thee away captive.
\p
\v 23 And he took up his parable, and said, Alas, who shall live when God doeth this!
\p
\v 24 And ships shall come from the coast of Chittim, and shall afflict Asshur, and shall afflict Eber, and he also shall perish for ever.
\p
\v 25 And Balaam rose up, and went and returned to his place: and Balak also went his way.
\c 25
\cl CHAPTER 25
\p
\v 1 A ND Israel abode in Shittim, and the people began to commit whoredom with the daughters of Moab.
\p
\v 2 And they called the people unto the sacrifices of their gods: and the people did eat, and bowed down to their gods.
\p
\v 3 And Israel joined himself unto Baal-peor: and the anger of the Lord was kindled against Israel.
\p
\v 4 And the LORD said unto Moses, Take all the heads of the people, and hang them up before the LORD against the sun, that the fierce anger of the Lord may be turned away from Israel.
\p
\v 5 And Moses said unto the judges of Israel, Slay ye every one his men that were joined unto Baal-peor.
\p
\v 6 And, behold, one of the children of Israel came and brought unto his brethren a Midianitish woman in the sight of Moses, and in the sight of all the congregation of the children of Israel, who were weeping before the door of the 1 tabernacle of the congregation.
\p
\v 7 And when.'Phinehas, the son of Eleazar, the son of Aaron the priest, saw it, he rose up from among the congregation, and took a javelin in his hand;
\p
\v 8 And he went after the man of Israel into the tent, and thrust both of them through, the man of Israel, and the woman through her body. So the yplague was stayed from the children of Israel.
\p
\v 9 And those that died in the plague were twenty and four thousand.
\p
\v 10 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 11 Phinehas,thesonofEleazar,the son of Aaron the priest, hath turned my wrath away from the children of Israel, while he was zealous for my sake among them, that I consumed not the children of Israel in my (jealousy.
\p
\v 12 Wherefore say, Behold, I give unto him my covenant of peace:
\p
\v 13 And he shall have it, and his seed after him, even the covenant of an everlasting priesthood; because he was zealous for his God, and made an atonement for the children of Israel.
\p
\v 14 Now the name of the Israelite that was slain, even that was slain with the Midianitish woman, was Zimri, the son of Salu, a prince of a chief house among the Simeonites.
\p
\v 15 And the name of the Midianitish woman that was slain was Cozbi, the daughter of !?Zur; he was head over a people, and of a chief house in Midian.
\p
\v 16 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 17 Vex the Midianites, and smite them:
\p
\v 18 For they vex you with their wiles, wherewith they have beguiled you in the matter of Peor, and in the matter of Cozbi, the daughter of a prince of Midian, their sister, who was slain in the day of the plague because of Peor.
\c 26
\cl CHAPTER 26
\p
\v 1 AND it came to pass after the plague, that the LORD spake unto Moses and unto Eleazar the son of Aaron the priest, saying,
\p
\v 2 Take the sum of all the congregation of the children of Israel, from twenty years old and upward, throughout their fathers' house, all that are able to go to war in Israel.
\p
\v 3 And Moses and Eleazar the priest spake with them in the plains of Moab by Jordan near .Jericho, saying,
\p
\v 4 Take the sum of the people, from twenty years old and upward; as tl Lord commanded Moses and the children of Israel, who went forth out of the and of Egypt.
\p
\v 5 Reuben, the eldest son of Israel: the children of Reuben; Hanoch, of whom Cometh the family of the Hanochites: of Pallu, the family of the Palluites:
\p
\v 6 Of Hezron, the family of the Hezronites: of Carmi, the family of the Carmites.
\p
\v 7 These are the families of the Reubenites: and they that were numbered of them were forty and three thousand and seven hundred and thirty.
\p
\v 8 And the sons of Pallu; Eliab.
\p
\v 9 And the sons of Eliab; Nemuel, and Dathan, and Abiram. These are that Dathan and Abiram, who were famous in the congregation, who strove against Moses and against Aaron in the company of Korah, when they strove against the Lord:
\p
\v 10 And the earth opened her tnouth, and swallowed them up together with Korah, when that company died, what time the fire devoured two hundred and fifty men: and they became a sign.
\p
\v 11 Notwithstanding the children of Korah died not.
\p
\v 12 The sons of Simeon after their families: of Nemuel, the family of the Nemuelites: of Jamin, the family of the Jaminites: of Jachin, the family ©f the Jachinites:
\p
\v 13 Of Zerah, the family of the Zarhites: of Shaul, the femily of the Shaulites.
\p
\v 14 These are the families of the Simeonites, twenty and two thousand and two hundred.
\p
\v 15 The children of Gad after their families: of Zephon, the family of the Zephonites: of Haggi, the family of the Haggites: of Shuni, the family of the Shunites:
\p
\v 16 Of Ozni, the family of the Oznites: of Eri, the family of the Erites:
\p
\v 17 Of Arod, the family of the «Arodites: of Areli, the family of the Arelites.
\p
\v 18 These are the families of the children of Gad according to those that were numbered of them, forty thousand and five hundred.
\p
\v 19 The sons of Judah were Er and Onan: and Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan.
\p
\v 20 And the sons of Judah after their families were; of 6’Shelah, the family of the Shelanites: of Pharez, the family of the Pharzites: of Zerah, the family of the Zarhites.
\p
\v 21 And the sons of Pharez were; of Hezron, the family of the Hezronites: of;'Hamul, the family of the Hamulites.
\p
\v 22 These are the families of Judah according to those that were numbered of them, threescore and sixteen thousand and five hundred.
\p
\v 23 Of the sons of -'Issachar after their families: o 'Tola, the family of the Tolaites: of Pua, the family of the Punites:
\p
\v 24 Of Jashub, the family of the Jashubites: of Shimron, the family of the Shimronites.
\p
\v 25 These are the families of Issachar according to those that were numbered of them, threescore and four thousand and three hundred.
\p
\v 26 O the sons of Zebulun after their families: of Sered, the family of the Sardites: of Elon, the family of the Elonites: of Jahleel, the family of the Jahleelites.
\p
\v 27 These are the families of the Zebulunites according to those that were numbered of them, threescore thousand and five hundred.
\p
\v 28 The sons of Joseph after their families were Manasseh and Ephraim.
\p
\v 29 Of the sons of Manasseh: of Machir, the family of the Machirites: and Machir begat Gilead: of Gilead come the family of the Gileadites.
\p
\v 30 These are the sons of Gilead: of Jeezer, the family of the Jeezerites: of Helek, the family of the Helekites:
\p
\v 31 And o Asriel, the family of the Asrielites: and of Shechem, the family of the Shechemites:
\p
\v 32 And of Shemida, the family of the Shemidaites: and of Hepher, the family of the Hepherites.
\p
\v 33 And Zelophehad the son of Hepher had no sons, but daughters: and the names of the daughters of Zelophehad were Mahlah, and Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.
\p
\v 34 These are the families of Manasseh, and those that were numbered of them, fifty and two thousand and seven hundred.
\p
\v 35 These are the sons of Ephraim after their families: of .? Shuthelah, the family of the Shuthalhites: of Becher.the family of the Bachrites: of Tahan, the family of the Tahanites.
\p
\v 36 And these aj-e the sons of Shuthelah: of Eran, the family of the Eranites.
\p
\v 37 These are the families of the sons of Ephraim according to those that were numbered of them, thirty and two thousand and five hundred. These are the sons of Joseph after their families.
\p
\v 38 The sons of . Benjamin after their families: of Bela, the family of the Belaites: of (Ashbel, the family of the Ashbelites: of Ahiram, the family of the Ahiramites:
\p
\v 39 Of Shupham, the family of the Shuphamites: of Hupham, the family of the Huphamites.
\p
\v 40 And the sons of Bela were Ard and Naaman: of 'Ard, the family of the Ardites: and of Naaman, the family of the Naamites.
\p
\v 41 These are the sons of Benjamin after their families: and they that were numbered of them were forty and five thousand and six hundred.
\p
\v 42 These are thesons of ? Dan after their families: of Shuham, the family of the Shuhamites. These are the families of Dan after their families.
\p
\v 43 All the families of the Shuhamites, according to those that were numbered of them, were threescore and four thousand and four hundred.
\p
\v 44 Of the children of Asher after their families: of Jimna, the family of the Jimnites: of Jesui, the family of the Jesuites: of Beriah, the family of the Beriites.
\p
\v 45 Of the sons of Beriah: of Heber, the family of the Heberites: of Malchiel, the family of the Malchielites.
\p
\v 46 And the name of the daughter of Asher was Sarah.
\p
\v 47 These are the families of the sons of Asher according to those that were numbered of them; who were fifty and three thousand and four hundred.
\p
\v 48 Of the sons of Naphtali after their families: of Jahzeel, the family of the Jahzeelites: of Guni, the family of the Gunites:
\p
\v 49 Of Jezer, the family of the Jezerites: of Shillem, the family of the Shillemites.
\p
\v 50 These are the families of Naphtali according to their families: and they that were numbered of them were forty and five thousand and four hundred.
\p
\v 51 These ivere the numbered of the children of Israel, six hundred thousand and a thousand seven hundred and thirty.
\p
\v 52 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 53 Unto these the land shall be divided for an inheritance according to the number of names.
\p
\v 54 To many thou shalt give the more inheritance, and to few thou shalt give the less inheritance: to every one shall his inheritance be given according to those that were numbered of him.
\p
\v 55 Notwithstanding the land shall be divided by lot: according to the names of the tribes of their fathers they shall inherit.
\p
\v 56 According to the lot shall the possession thereof be divided between many and few.
\p
\v 57 And these are they that were numbered of the Levites after their families: of Gershon. the family of the Gershonites: of Kohath, the family of the c’Kohathites: of Merari, the family of the Merarites.
\p
\v 58 These are the families of the Levites: the family of the Libnites, the family of the Hebronites, the family of the Mahlites, the family of the Mushites, the family of the Korathites. And Kohath begat Amram.
\p
\v 59 And the name of Amram’s wife was Jochebed, the daughter of Levi, whom her mother bare to Levi in Egypt: and she bare unto Amram Aaron and Moses, and Miriam their sister.
\p
\v 60 And unto Aaron were bom Na~ dab, and Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\p
\v 61 And Nadab and Abihu died, when they offered strange fire before the Lord.
\p
\v 62 And those that were numbered of them were twenty and three thousand, all males from a month old and upward; for they were not numbered among the children of Israel, because there was no inheritance given them among the children of Israel.
\p
\v 63 These are they that were numbered by Moses and Eleazar the priest, who numbered the children of Israel in the plains of Moab by •f Jordan near Jericho.
\p
\v 64 But among these there was not a man of them whom Moses and Aaron the priest numbered, when they numbered the children of Israel in the wilderness of Sinai.
\p
\v 65 For the LORD had said of them, They shall surely die in the wilderness. And there was not left a man of them, save Caleb the son of Jephunneh, and Joshua the son of •Nun.
\c 27
\cl CHAPTER 27
\p
\v 1 THEN came the daughters of Zelophehad, the son of Hepher, the son of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, of the families of Manasseh the son of Joseph: and these are the names of his daughters; Mahlah, Noah, and Hoglah, and Milcah, and .Tirzah.
\p
\v 2 And they stood before Moses, and before Eleazar the priest, and before the princes and all the congregation, by the door of the itabernacle of the congregation, saying,
\p
\v 3 Our father died in the wilderness, and he was not in the com.pany of them that gathered themselves together against the LORD in the company of J Korah; but died in his own sin, and had no sons.
\p
\v 4 Why should the name of our father be done away from among his family, because he hath no son? Give unto us therefore a possession among the brethren of our father.
\p
\v 5 And Moses brought their cause before the LORD.
\p
\v 6 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 7 The daughters of Zelophehad speak right: thou shalt surely give them a possession of an inheritance among their father’s brethren; and thou shalt cause the inheritance of their father to pass unto them.
\p
\v 8 And thou shalt speak unto the children of Israel, saying, If a man die, and have no son, then ye shall cause his inheritance to pass unto his daughter.
\p
\v 9 And if he have no daughter, then ye shall give his inheritance unto his brethren.
\p
\v 10 And if he have no brethren, then ye shall give his inheritance unto his father’s brethren.
\p
\v 11 And if his father have no brethren, then ye shall give his inheritance unto his kinsman that is next to him of his family, and he shall possess it: and it shall be unto the children of Israel a statute of judgment, as the Lord commanded Moses.
\p
\v 12 And the LORD said unto Moses, Get thee up into this mount -'Abarim, and see the land which I have given unto the children of Israel.
\p
\v 13 And when thou hast seen it, thou also shalt be gathered unto thy people, as ='' Aaron thy brother was gathered.
\p
\v 14 For ye rebelled against my commandment in the desert of Zin, in the strife of the congregation, to sanctify me at the water before their eyes: that is the water of Meribah in Kadesh in the wilderness of Zin.
\p
\v 15 And Moses spake unto the Lord, saying,
\p
\v 16 Let the LORD, the God of the spirits of all flesh, set a man over the congregation,
\p
\v 17 Which may go out before them, and which may go in before them, and which may lead them out, and which may bring them in; that the congregation of the LORD be not as sheep which have no shepherd.
\p
\v 18 And the LORD said unto Moses, Take thee Joshua the son of Nun, a man in whom is the spirit, and lay thine hand upon him;
\p
\v 19 And set him before Eleazar the priest, and before all the congregation; and give him a charge in their sight.
\p
\v 20 And thou shalt put some of thine honour upon him, that all the congregation of the children of Israel may be obedient.
\p
\v 21 And he shall stand before Eleazar the priest, who shall ask counsel for him after the judgment of Urim before the LORD: at his word shall they go out, and at his word they shall come in, both he, and all the children of Israel with him, even all the congregation.
\p
\v 22 And Moses did as the LORD commanded him: and he took .JJoshua, and set him before Eleazar the priest, and before all the congregation:
\p
\v 23 And he laid his hands upon him, and gave him a charge, as the Lord commanded by the hand of Moses.
\c 28
\cl CHAPTER 28
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, - saying,
\p
\v 2 Command the children of Israel, and say unto them. My offering, and my bread for my sacrifices made by fire, for a sweet savour unto me, shall ye observe to offer unto me in their due season.
\p
\v 3 And thou shalt say unto them, This is the offering made by fire which ye shall offer unto the LORD; two lambs of the first year without spot day by day, for a continual burnt offering.
\p
\v 4 The one lamb shalt thou offer in the morning, and the other lamb Shalt thou offer at even;
\p
\v 5 And a tenth part of sn ephah of flour for a meal offering, mingled with the fourth part of an hin of beaten oil.
\p
\v 6 It is a continual burnt offering, which was ordained in mount «Sinai for a sweet savour, a sacrifice made by fire unto the LORD.
\p
\v 7 And the drink offering thereof shall be the fourth part of an hin for the one lamb: in the holy place shalt thou cause the strong wine to be poured unto the LORD for a drink offering.
\p
\v 8 And the other lamb shalt thou offer at even: as the meal offering of the morning, and as the drink offering thereof, thou shalt offer it, a sacrifice made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the Lord.
\p
\v 9 And on the sabbath day two lambs of the first year without spot, and two tenth deals of flour for a meal offering, mingled with oil, and the drink offering thereof:
\p
\v 10 This is the burnt offering of every sabbath, beside the continual burnt offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 11 And in the beginnings of your months ye shall offer a burnt offering unto the Lord; two young bullocks, and one ram, seven lambs of the first year without spot;
\p
\v 12 And three tenth deals of flour for a meal offering, mingled with oil, for one bullock; and two tenth deals of flour for a meal offering, mingled with oil, for one ram;
\p
\v 13 And a several tenth deal of flour mingled with oil for a meal offering unto one lamb; for a burnt offering of a sweet savour, a sacrifice made by fire unto the LORD.
\p
\v 14 And their drink offerings shall be half an hin of wine unto a bullock, and the third part of an hin unto a ram, and the fourth pai’t of an hin unto a lamb: this is the burnt offering of every month throughout the months of the year.
\p
\v 15 And one kid of the goats for a sin offering unto the Lord shall be offered, beside the continual burnt offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 16 And in the fourteenth day of the first month is the passover of the Lord.
\p
\v 17 And in the fifteenth day of this month is the feast: seven days shall - unleavened bread be eaten.
\p
\v 18 In the first day shall be an holy convocation; ye shall do no manner of servile work therein:
\p
\v 19 But ye shall offer a sacrifice made by fire for a burnt offering unto the LORD; two young bullocks, and one ram, and seven lambs of the first year: they shall be unto you without blemish:
\p
\v 20 And their meal offering shall be ofhouT mingled with oil: chree tenth deals shall ye offer for a bullock, and two tenth deals for a ram;
\p
\v 21 A several tenth deal shalt thou offer for every lamb, throughout the seven lambs:
\p
\v 22 And one 'goat for a sin offering, to make an atonement for you.
\p
\v 23 Ye shall offer these beside the burnt offering in the morning, which is for a continual burnt offering.
\p
\v 24 After this manner ye shall offer daily, throughout the seven days, the food of the sacrifice made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the LORD: it shall be offered beside the continual burnt offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 25 And on the seventh day ye shall have an holy convocation; ye shall do no servile work.
\p
\v 26 Also in the day of the firstfruits, when ye bring a new meal offering unto the LORD, after your weeks be out, ye shall have an holy convocation; ye shall do no servile work:
\p
\v 27 But ye shall offer the burnt offering for a sweet savour unto the Lord; two young bullocks, one ram, seven lambs of the first year;
\p
\v 28 And their meal offering of flour mingled with oil, three tenth deals unto one bullock, two tenth deals unto one ram,
\p
\v 29 A several tenth deal unto one lamb, throughout the seven lambs;
\p
\v 30 And one kid of the goats, to make an atonement for you.
\p
\v 31 Ye shall offer them beside the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering, (they shall be unto you without blemish) and their drink offerings.
\c 29
\cl CHAPTER 29
\p
\v 1 AND in the seventh month, on - the first day of the month, ye shall have an holy convocation; ye shall do no servile work: it is a day of blowing the trumpets unto you.
\p
\v 2 And ye shall offer a burnt offering for a sweet savour unto the Lord; one young bullock, one ram, and seven lambs of the first year without blemish:
\p
\v 3 And their meal offering shall be
\p
\v 0 flour mingled with oil, three tenth deals for a bullock, and two tenth deals for a ram,
\p
\v 4 And one tenth deal for one lamb, throughout the seven lambs:
\p
\v 5 And one kid of the goats for a sin offering, to make an atonement for you:
\p
\v 6 Beside the burnt offering of the month, and the meal offering, and the daily burnt offering, and the meal offering, and their drink offerings, according unto their custom, for a sweet savour, a sacrifice made by fire unto the LORD.
\p
\v 7 And ye shall have on the tenth day of this seventh month an holy convocation; and ye shall afflict your souls: ye shall not do any work therein:
\p
\v 8 But ye shall offer a burnt offering unto the LORD or a sweet savour; one young bullock, one ram, and seven lambs of the first year; they shall be unto you without blemish:
\p
\v 9 And their meal offering shall be o flour mingled Vvdth oil, three tenth deals to a bullock, and two tenth deals to one ram,
\p
\v 10 A several tenth deal for one lamb, throughout the seven lambs:
\p
\v 11 One kid of the goats for a sin offering; beside the sin offering of atonement, and the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering of it, and their drink offerings.
\p
\v 12 And Jon the fifteenth day of the seventh month ye shall have an holy convocation; ye shall do no servile work, and ye shall keep a feast unto the Lord seven days:
\p
\v 13 And ye shall offer a burnt offering, a sacrifice made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the Lord; thirteen young bullocks, two .rams, and fourteen lambs of the first year; they shall be without blemish:
\p
\v 14 And their meal offering shall be of flour mingled with oil, three tenth deals unto every bullock of the thirteen bullocks, two tenth deals to each ram of the two rams,
\p
\v 15 And a several tenth deal to each lamb of the fourteen lambs:
\p
\v 16 And one kid of thegoats for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 17 And on the second day ye shall offer twelve young bullocks, two rams, fourteen lambs of the first year without spot:
\p
\v 18 And their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall he according to their number, -'after the custom:
\p
\v 19 And one kid of the goats for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering thereof, and their drink offerings.
\p
\v 20 And on the third day eleven bullocks, two rams, fourteen lambs of the first year without blemish;
\p
\v 21 And their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 22 And one goat for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 23 And on the fourth day ten bullocks, two rams, and fourteen lambs of the first year without blemish:
\p
\v 24 Their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 25 And one kid of the goats for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 26 And on the fifth day nine bullocks, two rams, and fourteen lambs of the first year without spot:
\p
\v 27 And their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 28 And one goat for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 29 And on the sixth day eight bullocks, two rams, and fourteen lambs of the first year without blemish:
\p
\v 30 And their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 31 And one goat or a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 32 And on the seventh day seven bullocks, two rams, and fourteen lambs of the first year without blemish:
\p
\v 33 And their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullocks, for the rams, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 34 And one goat or a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 35 On the eighth day ye shall have a solemn assembly: ye shall do no servile work therein:
\p
\v 36 But ye shall offer a burnt offering, a sacrifice made by fire, of a sweet savour unto the LORD: one bullock, one ram, seven lambs of the first year without blemish:
\p
\v 37 Their meal offering and their drink offerings for the bullock, for the ram, and for the lambs, shall be according to their number, after the custom:
\p
\v 38 And one goat for a sin offering; beside the continual burnt offering, and the meal offering, and the drink offering.
\p
\v 39 These things ye shall do unto the Lord in your set feasts, beside your vows, and your freewill offerings, for your burnt offerings, and for your meal offerings, and for your drink offerings, and for your peace offerings.
\p
\v 40 And Moses told the children of Israel according to all that the Lord commanded Moses.
\c 30
\cl CHAPTER 30
\p
\v 1 AND Moses spake unto the heads - of the tribes concerning the children of Israel, saying, This is the thing which the LORD hath commanded.
\p
\v 2 If a man vow a vow unto the Lord, or swear an oath to bind his soul with a bond; he shall not break his word, he shall do according to all that proceedeth out of his mouth.
\p
\v 3 If a woman also vow a vow unto the Lord, and bind herself by a bond, being in her father’s house in her youth;
\p
\v 4 And her father hear her vow, and her bond wherewith she hath bound her soul, and her father shall hold his peace at her: then all her vows shall stand, and every bond wherewith she hath bound her soul shall stand.
\p
\v 5 But if her father disallow her in the day that he heareth; not any of her vows, or of her bonds wherewith she hath bound her soul, shall stand: and the Lord shall forgive her, because her father disallowed her.
\p
\v 6 And if she had at all an husband, when she vowed, or uttered aught out of her lips, wherewith she bound her soul;
\p
\v 7 And her husband heard it, and held his peace at her in the day that he heard it: then her vows shall stand, and her bonds v. herewith she bound her soul shall stand.
\p
\v 8 But if her husband disallowed her on the day that he heard it; then he shall make her vow which she vowed, and that which she uttered with her lips, wherewith she bound her soul, of none effect: and the LORD shall forgive her.
\p
\v 9 But every vow of a widow, and of her that is divorced, wherewith they have bound their souls, shall stand against her.
\p
\v 10 And if she vowed in her husband’s house, or bound her soul by a bond with an oath;
\p
\v 11 And her husband heard it, and held his peace at her, and disallowed her not: then all her vows shall stand, and every bond wherewith she bound her soul shall stand.
\p
\v 13 But if her husband hath utterly made them void on the day he heard them; then whatsoever proceeded out of her lips concerning her vows, or concerning the bond of her soul, shall not stand: her husband hath made them void; and the LORD shall forgive her.
\p
\v 13 Every vow, and every binding oath to afflict the soul, her husband may establish it, or her husband may make it void.
\p
\v 14 But if her husband altogether hold his peace at her from day to day; then he establisheth all her VOWS, or all her bonds, which are upon her: he confirmeth them, because he held his peace at her in the day that he heard them.
\p
\v 15 But if he shall in aiy way make them void after that he hath heard them; then he shall bear her iniquity.
\p
\v 16 These are the statutes, which the Lord commanded Moses, between a man and his wife, between the father and his daughter, being yet in her youth in her father’s house.
\c 31
\cl CHAPTER 31
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, - saying,
\p
\v 2 Avenge the children of Israel of the Midianites: afterward shalt thou be gathered unto thy people.
\p
\v 3 And Moses spake unto the people, saying. Arm some of yourselves unto the war, and let them go against the Midianites, and avenge the Lord of Midian.
\p
\v 4 Of every tribe a thousand, throughout all the tribes of Israel, shall ye send to the war.
\p
\v 5 So there were delivered out of the thousands of Israel, a thousand of every tribe, twelve thousand armed for war.
\p
\v 6 And Moses sent them to the war, a thousand of every tribe, them and Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest, to the war, with the holy instruments, and the trumpets to blow in his hand.
\p
\v 7 And they warred against the Midianites, as the LORD commanded Bloses; and they slew all the males.
\p
\v 8 And they slew the kings of Midian, beside the rest of them that were slain; namely, Evi, and Rekem, and sZmt, and Hur, and Reba, five kings of Midian: Balaam also the son of Beor they slew with the sword.
\p
\v 9 And the children of Israel took all the women of Midian captives, and their little ones, and took the spoil of all their cattle, and all their flocks, and all their goods.
\p
\v 10 And they burnt all their cities wherein they dwelt, and all their goodly castles, with fire.
\p
\v 11 And they took all the spoil, and all the prey, both of men and of beasts.
\p
\v 12 And they brought the captives, and the prey, and the spoil, unto Moses, and Eleazar the priest, and I unto the congregation of the children of Israel, unto the camp at the plains of Moab, which are by Jordan near Jericho.
\p
\v 13 And Moses, and Eleazar the priest, and all the princes of the congregation, went forth to meet them without the camp.
\p
\v 14 And Moses was wroth with the ofiicers of the host, with the captains over thousands, and captains over hundreds, that came from the battle.
\p
\v 15 And Moses said unto them. Have ye saved all the women alive ?
\p
\v 16 Behold, these caused the children of Israel, through the counsel of Balaam, to commit trespass against the Lord in the matter of Peor, and there was a plague among the congregation of the Lord.
\p
\v 17 Now therefore kill every male among the little ones, and kill every woman that hath known man by lying with him.
\p
\v 18 But all the women children, that have not known a man by lying with him, keep alive for yotu-selves.
\p
\v 19 And do ye abide without the camp seven days: whosoever hath killed any person, and whosoever hath touched any slain, purify both yourselves and your captives on the third day, and on the seventh day.
\p
\v 20 And purify all your raiment, and all that is made of skins, and all work of goats' hair, and all things made of wood.
\p
\v 21 And Eleazar the priest said unto the men of war that went to the battle. This is the ordinance of the law which the Lord commanded Moses;
\p
\v 22 Only the gold, and the silver, the brass, the iron, the tin, and the lead,
\p
\v 23 Every thing that may abide the fire, ye shall make it go through the fire, and it shall be clean: nevertheless it shall be purified with the water of separation: and all that abideth not the fire ye shall make go through the water.
\p
\v 24 And ye shall wash your clothes on the seventh day, and ye shall be clean, and afterward ye shall come into the camp.
\p
\v 25 And the LORD spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 26 Take the sum of the prey that was taken, both of man and of beast, thou, and YAQazaX the priest, and the chief fathers of the congregation:
\p
\v 27 And divide the prey into two parts; between them that took the war upon them, who went out to battle, and between all the congregation:
\p
\v 28 And levy a tribute unto the Lord of the men of war that went out to battle: one soul of five hundred, both of the persons, and of the beeves, and of the asses, and of the sheep:
\p
\v 29 Take it of their half, and give it unto Eleazar the priest, for an heave offering of the LORD.
\p
\v 30 And of the children of Israel’s half, thou Shalt take one portion of fifty, of the persons, of the beeves, of the asses, and of the flocks, of all manner of beasts, and give them unto the Levites, which keep the charge of the ifabemacle of the Lord.
\p
\v 31 And Moses and Eleazar the priest did as the LORD commanded Moses.
\p
\v 32 And the booty, being the rest of the prey which the men of war had caught, was six hundred thousand and seventy thousand and five thousand sheep,
\p
\v 33 And threescore and twelve thousand beeves,
\p
\v 34 And threescore and one thousand asses,
\p
\v 35 And thirty and two thousand persons in all, of women that had not known man by lying with him.
\p
\v 36 And the half, which was the portion of them that went out to war, was in number three hundred thousand and seven and thirty thousand and five hundred sheep:
\p
\v 37 And the LORD’S tribute of the sheep was six hundred and threescore and fifteen.
\p
\v 38 And the beeves were thirty and six thousand; of which the LORD’S tribute was threescore and twelve.
\p
\v 39 And the asses were thirty thousand and five hundred; of which the Lord’s tribute was threescore and one.
\p
\v 40 And the persons were sixteen thousand; of whom the LORD’S tribute was thirty and two persons.
\p
\v 41 And Moses gave the tribute, which was the LORD’S heave offering, unto Eleazar the priest, as the Lord commanded Moses.
\p
\v 42 And of the children of Israel’s half, which Moses divided from the men that warred,
\p
\v 43 (Now the half that pertained unto the congregation was three hundred thousand and thirty thousand and seven thousand and five hundred sheep,
\p
\v 44 And thirty and six thousand beeves,
\p
\v 45 And thitty thousand asses and five hundred,
\p
\v 46 And sixteen thousand persons;)
\p
\v 47 Even of the children of Israel’s half, Moses took one portion of fifty, both of man and of beast, and gave them unto the Levites, that kept the charge of the tabernacle of the Lord; as the Lord commanded Moses.
\p
\v 48 And the officers that were over thousands of the host, the captains of thousands, and captains of hundreds, came near unto Moses:
\p
\v 49 And they said unto Moses, Thy servants have taken the sum of the men of war that are under our charge, and there lacketh not one man of us.
\p
\v 50 We have therefore brought an oblation for the LORD, what ever man hath gotten, of jewels of gold, chains, and bracelets, rings, earrings, and tablets, to make an atonement for our souls before the Lord.
\p
\v 51 And Moses and Eleazar the priest took the gold of them, even all wrought jewels.
\p
\v 52 And all the gold of the offering that they offered up to the LORD, ot the captains of thousands, and of the captains of hundreds, was sixteen thousand seven hundred and fifty shekels.
\p
\v 53 (For the men of war had taken spoil, every man for himself.)
\p
\v 54 And Moses and Eleazar the priest took the gold of the captains of thousands and of hundreds, and brought it into the stabernacle of the congregation, for a memorial for the children of Israel before the LORD.
\c 32
\cl CHAPTER 32
\p
\v 1 NOW the children of «= Reuben and the children of Gad had a very great multitude of cattle: and when they saw the land of Jazer, and the land of Gilead, that, behold, the place was a place for cattle;
\p
\v 2 The children of Gad and the children of Reuben came and spake unto Moses, and to Eleazar the priest, and unto the princes of the congregation, saying,
\p
\v 3 Ataroth, and .'Dibon, and Jazer, and Nimrah, and Heshbon, and Elealeh, and Shebara, and JNebo, and Beon,
\p
\v 4 Even the country which the Lord smote before the congregation of Israel, is a land for cattle, and thy servants have cattle:
\p
\v 5 Wherefore, said they, if we have found grace in thy sight, let this land be given unto thy servants for a possession, and bring us not over Jordan.
\p
\v 6 And Bloses said unto the children of Gad and to the children of Reuben, Shall your brethren go to war, and shall ye sit here ?
\p
\v 7 And wherefore discourage ye the heart of the children of Israel from going over into the land which the Lord hath given them ?
\p
\v 8 Thus did your fathers, when I sent them from Kadesh-bamea to see the land.
\p
\v 9 For when they went up unto the valley of Eshcol, and saw the land, they discouraged the heart of the children of Israel, that they should not go into the land which the LORD had given them.
\p
\v 10 And the LORD’S anger was kindled the same time, and he sware, saying,
\p
\v 11 Surely none of the men that came up out of Egypt, from twenty j years old and upward, shall see the j 'land which I sware unto Abra-' ham, unto Isaac, and unto Jacob; because they have not wholly followed me:
\p
\v 12 Save Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenezite,and Joshua the son of - Nun: for they have wholly followed the LORD.
\p
\v 13 And the Lord’s anger was kindled against Israel, and he made them wander in the wilderness forty years, until all the generation, that had done evil in the sight of the j Lord, was consumed. !
\p
\v 14 And, behold, ye are risen up in , your fathers' stead, an increase of sinful men, to augment yet the 1 fierce anger of the LORD toward Israel. ,
\p
\v 15 For if ye turn away from after him, he will yet again leave them in I the wilderness; and ye shall destroy all this people.
\p
\v 16 And they came near unto him,; and said. We will build sheepfolds here for our cattle, and cities for our little ones:
\p
\v 17 But we ourselves will go ready armed before the children of Israel, until we have brought them unto their place; and our little ones shall dwell in the fenced cities because of the inhabitants of the land.
\p
\v 18 We will not return unto our houses, until the children of Israel have inherited every man his inheritance.
\p
\v 19 For we will not inherit with them on yonder side - Jordan, or forward j because our inheritance is fallen to us on this side Jordan eastward.
\p
\v 20 And Moses said unto them. If ye will do this thing, if ye will go armed before the Lord to war,
\p
\v 21 And will go all of you armed over Jordan before the LORD, until he hath driven out his enemies from before him,
\p
\v 22 And the land be subdued before the Lord: then afterward ye shall return, and be guiltless before the Lord, and before Israel; and this land shall be your possession before the Lord.
\p
\v 23 But if ye will not do so, behold, ye have sinned against the Lord: and be sure your sin will find you out.
\p
\v 24 Build you cities for your little ones, and folds for your sheep; and do that which hath proceeded out of your mouth.
\p
\v 25 And the children of Gad and the children of Reuben spake unto Moses, saying. Thy servants will do as my lord commandeth.
\p
\v 26 Our little ones, our wives, our flocks, and all our cattle, shall be there in the cities of Gilead:
\p
\v 27 But thy servants will pass over, every man armed for war, before the Lord to battle, as my lord saith.
\p
\v 28 So concerning them Moses commanded Eleazar the priest, and Joshua the son of Nun, and the chief fathers of the tribes of the children of Israel:
\p
\v 29 And Moses said unto them. If the children of Gad and the children of Reuben will pass with you over Jordan, every man armed to battle, before the LORD, and the land shall be subdued before you; then ye shall give them the land of Gilead for a possession:
\p
\v 30 But if they will not pass over with you armed, they shall have possessions among you in the land of ? Canaan.
\p
\v 31 And the children of Gad and the children of Reuben answered, saying, As the Lord hath said unto thy servants, so will we do.
\p
\v 32 We will pass over armed before the Lord into the land of Canaan, that the possession of our inheritance on this side Jordan may he ours.
\p
\v 33 And Moses gave unto them, even to the children of Gad, and to the children of Reuben, and unto half the tribe of Manasseh the son of z Joseph, the kingdom ol. Sihon king of the Amorites, and the kingdom of Og king of Bashan, the »na.nd, with the cities thereof in the coasts, even the cities of the country round about.
\p
\v 34 And the children of Gad built Dibon, and Ataroth, and Aroer,
\p
\v 35 And Atroth, Shophan, and Jaazer, and Jogbehah,
\p
\v 36 And Beth-nimrah, and Bethharan, fenced cities: and folds for sheep.
\p
\v 37 And the children of Reuben built Heshbon, and Eleaieh, and Kirjathaim,
\p
\v 38 And Nebo, and Baal-meon, (their names being changed,) and Shibmah: and gave other names unto the cities which they builded.
\p
\v 39 And the children of Machir the son of Manasseh went to Gilead, and took it, and dispossessed the Amorite that was in it.
\p
\v 40 And Moses gave Gilead unto Machir the son of Manasseh; and he dwelt therein.
\p
\v 41 And Jair the son of Manasseh went and took the small towns thereof, and called them JHavothjair.
\p
\v 42 And Nobah went and took Kenath, and the villages thereof, and called it Nobah, after his ovn
\c 33
\cl CHAPTER 33
\p
\v 1 THESE are the journeys of the children of Israel, who went forth out of the land of Egypt with their armies under the hand of Moses and Aaron.
\p
\v 2 And Moses wrote their goings out according to their journeys by the commandment of the LORD: and these are their journeys according to their goings out.
\p
\v 3 And tbey departed from Rameses in the first month, on the fifteenth day of the first month; on the morrow after the passover the children of Israel went out with an high hand in the sight of ail the Egyptians.
\p
\v 4 For the Egyptians buried all their firstborn, whom the LORD had smitten among them: upon their gods also the LORD executed judgments.
\p
\v 5 And the children of Israel removed from Rameses, and pitched in 'Succoth.
\p
\v 6 And they departed from Succoth, and pitched in Etham, which is in the edge of the wilderness.
\p
\v 7 And they removed from Etham, and turned again unto Pi-hahiroth, which is before J Baal-zephon: and they pitched before Migdol.
\p
\v 8 And they departed from before Pi-hahiroth, and passed through the midst of the sea into the wilderness, and went three days' journey in the wilderness of Etham, and pitched in Marah.
\p
\v 9 And they removed from Marah, and came unto Elim: and in Elim were twelve fountains of water, and threescore and ten palm trees; and they pitched there.
\p
\v 10 And they removed from Elim, and encamped by the Red Sea.
\p
\v 11 And they removed from the Red Sea, and encamped in the wilderness of Sin.
\p
\v 12 And they took their journey out of the wilderness of Sin, and encamped in Dophkah.
\p
\v 13 And they departed from Dophkah, and encamped in Aiush.
\p
\v 14 And they removed from Alush, and encamped at Rephidim, where was no water for the people to drink.
\p
\v 15 And they departed from Rephidim, and pitched in the wilderness of Sinai.
\p
\v 16 And they removed from the desert of Sinai, and pitched at Kibrothhattaavah.
\p
\v 17 And they departed from Kibroth-hattaavah, and encamped at Hazeroth.
\p
\v 18 And they departed from Hazeroth, and pitched in Rithmah.
\p
\v 19 And they departed from Rithmah, and pitched at Rimmon-parez.
\p
\v 20 And they departed from Rimmon-parez, and pitched in Libnah.
\p
\v 21 And they removed from Libnah, and pitched at Rissah.
\p
\v 22 And they journeyed from Rissah, and pitched in Kehelathah.
\p
\v 23 And they went from Kehelathah, and pitched in mount Shapher.
\p
\v 24 And they removed from mount Shapher, and encamped in Haradah.
\p
\v 25 And they removed from Haradah, and pitched in Makheloth.
\p
\v 26 And they removed from Blakheloth, and encrmped at Tahath.
\p
\v 27 And they departed from Tahatli, and pitched at Tarah.
\p
\v 28 And they removed from Tarah, and pitched in Mithcah.
\p
\v 29 And they went from Mithcah, and pitched in Hashmonah.
\p
\v 30 And they departed from Hashmonah, and encamped at Moseroth.
\p
\v 31 And they departed from Moseroth, and pitched in Bene-jaakan.
\p
\v 32 And they removed from Benejaakan, and encamped at Hor-hagidgad.
\p
\v 33 And they went from Hor-hagidgad, and pitched in Jotbathah,
\p
\v 34 And they removed from Jotbathah, and encamped at Ebronah.
\p
\v 35 And they departed from Ebronah, and encamped at Ezion-gaber.
\p
\v 36 And they removed fromEziongaber, and pitched in the wilderness of Zin, which is Kadesh.
\p
\v 37 And they removed from Kadesh, and pitched in mount Hor, in the edge of the =land of Edom.
\p
\v 38 And Aaron the priest went up into mount Hor at the commandment of the Lord, and died there, in the fortieth year after the children ofilsrael were come out of the land of Egypt, in the first day of the fifth month.
\p
\v 39 And Aaron was an hundred and twenty and three years old when he died in mount Hor.
\p
\v 40 And king Arad the Canaanite, which dwelt in the south in the land of Canaan, heard of the coming of the children of Israel.
\p
\v 41 And they departed from mount Hor, and pitched in Zalmonah.
\p
\v 42 And they departed from Zalmonah, and pitched in Funon.
\p
\v 43 And they departed from Punon, and pitched in Oboth.
\p
\v 44 And they departed from Oboth, and pitched in .Ije-abarim, in the border of Moab.
\p
\v 45 And they departed from Em, and pitched in Dibon-gad.
\p
\v 46 And they removed from Dibongad, and encamped in Almon-diblathaim.
\p
\v 47 And they removed from Almondiblathaim, and pitched in the mountains of yAbarim, before Nebo.
\p
\v 48 And they departed from the mountains of Abarim, and pitched in the plains of Moab by -'Jordan near Oericho.
\p
\v 49 And they pitched by Jordan, from Beth-jesimoth even unto Abel-shittim in the plains of Moab. Moses in the plains of Moab by Jordan near Jericho, saying,
\p
\v 51 Speak unto the children of Israel, and say unto them, When ye are passed over Jordan into the land of Canaan;
\p
\v 52 Then ye shall drive out all the inhabitants of the land from before you, and destroy all their pictures, and destroy all their molten images, and quite pluck down all their high places:
\p
\v 53 And ye shall dispossess the inhabitants of the land, and dwell therein: for I have given you the land to possess it.
\p
\v 54 And ye shall divide the land by lot for an inheritance among your families: and to the more ye shall give the more inheritance, and to the fewer ye shall give the less inheritance: every man’s inheritance shall be in the place where his lot falleth; according to the tribes of your fathers ye shall inherit.
\p
\v 55 But if ye will not drive out the inhabitants of the land from before you; then it shall come to pass, that those whom ye let remain of them shall be pricks in your eyes, and thorns in your sides, and shall vex you in the land wherein ye dwell.
\p
\v 56 Moreover it shall come to pass, that I shall do unto you, as I thought to do unto them.
\c 34
\cl CHAPTER 34
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses, - saying,
\p
\v 2 Command the children of Israel, and say unto them, When ye come into the land of Canaan; (this is the land that shall fall unto you for an inheritance, even the land of Canaan with the borders thereof:)
\p
\v 3 Then your south quarter shall be from the wilderness of Zin along by the coast of Edom, and your south border shall be the outmost coast of the Salt Sea eastward:
\p
\v 4 And your border shall turn from the south to the ascent of Akrabbim, and pass on to Zin: and the going forth thereof shall be from the south to Kadesh-barnea, and shall go on to Hazar-addar, and pass on to .Azmon:
\p
\v 5 And the border shall fetch a compass from Azmon unto the river of Egypt, and the goings out of it shall be at the sea.
\p
\v 6 And as for the western border, ye shall even have the great sea for a border: this shall be your west border.
\p
\v 7 And this shall be your north border: from the great sea ye shall point out for you mount Hor:
\p
\v 8 From mount Hor ye shall point out your border unto the entrance ofyHamath; and the goings forth of the border shall be to Zedad:
\p
\v 9 And the border shall go on to Ziphron, and the goings out of it shall be at -'Hazar-enan: this shall be your north border.
\p
\v 10 And ye shall point out your east border from Hazar-enan to Shepham:
\p
\v 11 And the coast shall go down from Shepham to Riblah, on the east side of Ain; and the border shall descend, and shall reach unto the side of the Sea of Chinnereth eastward:
\p
\v 12 And the border shall go down to Jordan, and the goings out of it shall be at the Salt Sea: this shall be your land with the coasts thereof round about.
\p
\v 13 And Moses commanded the children of Israel, saying, This is the land which ye shall inherit by lot, which the LORD commanded to give unto the nine tribes, and to the half tribe:
\p
\v 14 For the tribe of the children of Reuben according to the house of their fathers, and the tribe of the children of Gad according to the house of their fathers, have received their inheritance; and half the tribe of Manasseh have received their inheritance:
\p
\v 15 The two tribes and the half tribe have received their inheritance on this side Jordan near Jericho eastward, toward the sunrising.
\p
\v 16 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 17 These are the names of the men who shall divide the land unto you: Eleazar the priest, and Joshua the son of JNun.
\p
\v 18 And ye shall take one prince of every tribe, to divide the land by inheritance.
\p
\v 19 And the names of the men are these: Of the tribe of Judah, Caleb the son of Jephunneh.
\p
\v 20 And of the tribe of the children of Simeon, Shemuel the son of Ammihud.
\p
\v 21 Of the tribe of Benjamin, Elidad the son of Chislon.
\p
\v 22 And the prince of the tribe of the children of Dan, Bukki the son of Jogli.
\p
\v 23 The prince of the children of Joseph, for the tribe of the children of Manasseh, Hanniel the son of Ephod.
\p
\v 24 And the prince of the tribe of the children of Ephraim, Kemuel the son of Shiphtan.
\p
\v 25 And the prince of the tribe of the children of .Zebulun, Elizaphan the son of Parnach.
\p
\v 26 And the prince of the tribe of the children of Issachar, Paltiel the son of Azzan.
\p
\v 27 And the prince of the tribe of the children of Asher, -'Ahihud the son of Shelomi.
\p
\v 28 And the prince of the tribe of the children of Naphtali, Pedahel the son of Ammihud.
\p
\v 29 These are they whom the LORD commanded to divide the inheritance unto the children of Israel in the land of Canaan.
\c 35
\cl CHAPTER 35
\p
\v 1 AND the Lord spake unto Moses - in the plains of Moab by Jordan near Jericho, saying,
\p
\v 2 Command the children of Israel, that they give unto the Levites of the inheritance of their possession cities to dwell in; and ye shall give also unto the Levites suburbs for the cities round about them.
\p
\v 3 And the cities shall they have to dwell in; and the suburbs of them shall be for their cattle, and for their goods, and for all their beasts.
\p
\v 4 And the suburbs of the cities, which ye shall give unto the Levites, shall reach from the wall of the city and outward a thousand cubits round about.
\p
\v 5 And ye shall measure from without the city on the east side two thousand cubits, and on the south side two thousand cubits, and on the west side two thousand cubits, and on the north side two thousand cubits; and the city shall be in the midst: this shall be to them the suburbs of the cities.
\p
\v 6 And among the cities which ye shall give unto the Levites there shall be six cities for refuge, which ye shall appoint for the manslayer, that he may flee thither: and to them ye shall add forty and two cities.
\p
\v 7 So all the cities which ye shall give to the Levites shall be forty and eight cities: them shall ye give with their suburbs
\p
\v 8 And the cities which ye shall give shall he of the possession of the children of Israel: from them that have many ye shall take many; but from them that have few ye shall take few: every one shall give of his cities unto the Levites according to his inheritance which he inheriteth.
\p
\v 9 And the Lord spake unto Moses, saying,
\p
\v 10 Speak unto the children of Israel, and say unto them, When ye be come over Jordan into the land ofi’Canaan;
\p
\v 11 Then ye shall appoint you cities to be cities of refuge for you; that the manslayer may flee thither, which killeth any person without intention.
\p
\v 12 And they shall be unto you cities for refuge from the avenger; that the manslayer die not, until he stand before the congregation in judgment.
\p
\v 13 And of these cities which ye shall give six cities shall ye have for refuge.
\p
\v 14 Ye shall give three cities on this side Jordan, and three cities shall ye give in the land of Canaan, which shall be cities of refuge.
\p
\v 15 These six cities shall be a refuge, both for the children of Israel, and for the stranger, and for the sojourner among them: that every one that killeth any person without intention may flee thither.
\p
\v 16 And if he smite him with an instrument of iron, so that he die, he IS a miu’derer: the murderer shall surely be put to death.
\p
\v 17 And if he smite him with throwing a stone, wherewith he may die, and he die, he is a J murderer: the murderer shall surely be put to death.
\p
\v 18 Or if he smite him with an hand weapon of wood, wherewith he may die, and he die, he is a murderer: the murderer shall surely be put to death.
\p
\v 19 The avenger of blood himself shall slay the murderer: when he meeteth him, he shall slay him.
\p
\v 20 But if he thrust him of hatred, or hurl at him by laying of wait, that he die;
\p
\v 21 Or in enmity smite him with his hand, that he die: he that smote him. shall surely be put to death; for he is a murderer: the avenger of blood shall slay the murderer, when he meeteth him.
\p
\v 22 But if he thrust him suddenly without enmity, or have cast upon him any thing without laying of wait,
\p
\v 23 Or with any stone, wherewith a man may die, seeing him not, and cast it upon him, that he die, and was not his enemy, neither sought his harm:
\p
\v 24 Then the congregation shall judge between the manslayer and the avenger of blood according to these judgments:
\p
\v 25 And the congregation shall deliver the manslayer out of the hand of the avenger of blood, and the congregation shall restore him to the city of his refuge, whither he was fled: and he shall abide in it unto the death of the high priest, which was anointed with the holy oil.
\p
\v 26 But if the manslayer shall at any time come without the border of the city of his refuge, whither he was fled;
\p
\v 27 And the avenger of blood find him without the borders of the city of his refuge, and the avenger of blood kill the manslayer; he shall not be guilty of blood:
\p
\v 28 Because he should have remained in the city of his refuge until the death of the high priest: but after the death of the high priest the manslayer shall retmn into the Hand of his possession.
\p
\v 29 So these things shall be for a statute of judgment unto you throughout your generations in all your dwellings.
\p
\v 30 Whoso killeth any person, the murderer shall be put to death by the mouth of witnesses: but one witness shall not testify against any person to cause him to die.
\p
\v 31 Moreover ye shall take no compensation for the life of a murderer, who is guilty of death: but he shall be surely put to death.
\p
\v 32 And ye shall take no compensation for him that is fled to the city of his refuge, that he should come again to dwell in the land, until the death of the priest.
\p
\v 33 So ye shall not pollute the land wherein ye are: for blood it defileth the land: and the land cannot be cleansed of the blood that is shed therein, but by the blood of him that shed it.
\p
\v 34 Defile not therefore the land which ye shall inhabit, wherein I dwell: for I the LORD dwell among the children of Israel.
\c 36
\cl CHAPTER 36
\p
\v 1 AND the chief fathers of the fa- milies of the children of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, of the families of the sons of Joseph, came near, and spake before Moses, and before the princes, the chief fathers of the children of Israel:
\p
\v 2 And they said, The LORD commanded my lord to give the land for an inheritance by lot to the children of Israel: and my lord was commanded by the Lord to give the inheritance of Zelophehadour brother unto his daughters.
\p
\v 3 And if they be married to any of the sons of the other tribes of the children of Israel, then shall their inheritance be taken from the inheritance of our fathers, and shall be put to the inheritance of the tribe whereunto they are received: so shall it be taken from the lot of our inheritance.
\p
\v 4 And when the jubilee of the children of Israel shall be, then shall their inheritance be put unto the inheritance of the tribe whereunto they are received: so shall their inheritance be taken away from the inheritance of the tribe of our fathers.
\p
\v 5 And Moses commanded the children of Israel according to the word of the Lord, saying. The tribe of the sons of Joseph hath said well.
\p
\v 6 This is the thing which the Lord doth command concerning the daughters of Zelophehad, saying, Let them marry to whom they think best; only to the family of the tribe of their father shall they marry.
\p
\v 7 So shall not the inheritance of the children of Israel remove from tribe to tribe: for every one of the children of Israel shall keep himself to the inheritance of the tribe of his fathers.
\p
\v 8 And every daughter, that possesseth an inheritance in any tribe of the children of Israel, shall be wife unto one of the family of the tribe of her father, that the children of Israel may enjoy every man the inheritance of his fathers.
\p
\v 9 Neither shall the inheritance remove from one tribe to another tribe; but every one of the tribes of the children of Israel shall keep himself to his own inheritance.
\p
\v 10 Even as the Lord commanded Moses, so did the daughters of Zelophehad:
\p
\v 11 For Mahlah, 6Tirzah, .nd Hoglah, and Milcah, and Noah,the daughters of Zelophehad, were married unto their father’s brothers' sons:
\p
\v 12 And they were married into the families of the sons of Manasseh the son of Joseph, and their inheritance rem.ained in the tribe of the family of their father.
\p
\v 13 These are the commandments and the judgments, which the LORD commanded by the hand of Moses unto the children of Israel in the plains of Moab by Jordan near Jericho.
